# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: crimean-tatar-alphabet
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In February and March 2014, Russia invaded the Crimean Peninsula, part of Ukraine, and then annexed it.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] This took place in the relative power vacuum immediately following the Revolution of Dignity.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] It marked the beginning of the Russo-Ukrainian war.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The events in Kyiv that ousted Ukrainian president Viktor Yanukovych on 22 February 2014 sparked both pro-Russian and anti-separatism demonstrations in Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] At the same time, Russian president Vladimir Putin told his security chiefs to begin work on "returning Crimea to Russia".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 27 February, Russian special forces without insignia seized strategic sites across Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Russia at first denied involvement, but Putin later admitted that they were Russian troops.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] As the armed men occupied Crimea's parliament, it dismissed the Crimean government, installed the pro-Russian Aksyonov government, and announced a referendum on Crimea's status.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The referendum was held under Russian occupation and, according to the Russian-installed authorities, the result was overwhelmingly in favor of joining Russia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The next day, 17 March 2014, Crimea's authorities declared independence and requested to join Russia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Russia formally incorporated Crimea on 18 March 2014 as the Republic of Crimea and federal city of Sevastopol.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Following the annexation, Russia militarized the peninsula and warned against any outside intervention.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Ukraine and many other countries condemned the annexation and consider it to be a violation of international law and Russian agreements safeguarding the territorial integrity of Ukraine.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The annexation led to the other members of the G8 suspending Russia from the group and introducing sanctions.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The United Nations General Assembly also rejected the referendum and annexation, adopting a resolution affirming the "territorial integrity of Ukraine within its internationally recognised borders", and referring to the Russian action as a "temporary occupation".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The Russian government opposes the "annexation" label, with Putin defending the referendum as complying with the principle of the self-determination of peoples.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The names of the Crimean annexation vary.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Crimea was part of the Crimean Khanate from 1441 until it was annexed by the Russian Empire in 1783 by a decree of Catherine the Great.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] After the downfall of Russian empire in 1917 during the first stages of the Russian Civil War there were a series of short-lived independent governments (Crimean People's Republic, Crimean Regional Government, Crimean SSR).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] They were followed by White Russian governments (General Command of the Armed Forces of South Russia and later South Russian Government).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In October 1921, the Bolshevik Russian SFSR gained control of the peninsula and instituted the Crimean Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic as a member of Russian Federation.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In the following year Crimea joined the Soviet Union as a part of Russia (the RSFSR).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] After the Second World War and the 1944 deportation of all of the indigenous Crimean Tatars by the Soviet government, the Crimean ASSR was stripped of its autonomy in 1946 and downgraded to the status of an oblast of the Russian SFSR.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In 1954, the Crimean Oblast was transferred from the Russian SFSR to the Ukrainian SSR by decree of the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet of the Soviet Union to commemorate the 300th anniversary of Ukraine's union with Russia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In 1989, under Gorbachev's perestroika, the Supreme Soviet declared that the deportation of the Crimean Tatars under Stalin had been illegal and the mostly Muslim ethnic group was allowed to return to Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In 1990, the Soviet of the Crimean Oblast proposed the restoration of the Crimean ASSR.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The oblast conducted a referendum in 1991, which asked whether Crimea should be elevated into a signatory of the New Union Treaty (that is, become a union republic on its own).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] By that time, though, the dissolution of the Soviet Union was well underway.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The Crimean ASSR was restored for less than a year as part of Ukrainian SSR before the restoration of Ukrainian independence.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Newly independent Ukraine maintained Crimea's autonomous status, while the Supreme Council of Crimea affirmed the peninsula's "sovereignty" as a part of Ukraine.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The confrontation between the government of Ukraine and Crimea deteriorated between 1992 and 1995.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In May 1992 the regional parliament declared an independent "Crimean republic." In June 1992, the parties reached a compromise, that Crimea would have considerable autonomy but remain part of Ukraine.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Yuri Meshkov, a leader of the Russian movement was elected President of Crimea in 1994 and his party won a majority in the regional parliamentary elections in the same year.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The pro-Russian movement was then weakened by internal disagreements and in March 1995 the Ukrainian government gained the upper hand.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The office of the elected President of Crimea was abolished and a loyal head of region was installed instead of Meshkov; the 1992 constitution and a number of local laws were repealed.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] According to Gwendolyn Sasse the conflict was defused due to Crimea's multi-ethnic population, fractures within the pro-Russian movement, Kyiv's policy of avoiding escalation and the lack of active support from Russia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] During the 1990s, the serious dispute over control of the Black Sea Fleet and Crimean naval facilities, as well as the status of Crimea in whole were source of tensions between Russia and Ukraine.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In 1992, Vladimir Lukin, then chairman of the Russian Duma's Committee on Foreign Affairs, suggested that in order to pressure Ukraine to give up its claim to the Black Sea Fleet, Russia should question Ukrainian control over Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In 1998 the Partition Treaty divided the fleet and gave Russia a naval base in Sevastopol, and the Treaty of Friendship recognized the inviolability of existing borders.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] However, in 2003 Tuzla Island conflict issues over maritime border resurfaced.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In September 2008, the Ukrainian Foreign Minister Volodymyr Ohryzko accused Russia of giving Russian passports to the population in Crimea, and described it as a "real problem", given Russia's declared policy of military intervention abroad to protect Russian citizens.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 24 August 2009, anti-Ukrainian demonstrations were held in Crimea by ethnic Russian residents.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Sergei Tsekov (of the Russian Bloc and then deputy speaker of the Crimean parliament) said then that he hoped that Russia would treat Crimea the same way as it had treated South Ossetia and Abkhazia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Crimea is populated by an ethnic Russian majority and a minority of both ethnic Ukrainians and Crimean Tatars, and thus demographically possessed one of Ukraine's largest ethnically Russian populations.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] As early as in 2010, some analysts already speculated that the Russian government had irredentist plans.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Taras Kuzio said that "Russia has an even more impossible time recognizing Ukraine's sovereignty over the Crimea and the port of Sevastopol – as seen by public opinion in Russia, statements by politicians, including members of the ruling United Russia party, experts and journalists".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In 2011, William Varettoni wrote that "Russia wants to annex Crimea and is merely waiting for the right opportunity, most likely under the pretense of defending Russian brethren abroad".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The Euromaidan protest movement began in Kyiv in late November 2013 after President Viktor Yanukovych, of the Party of Regions, failed to sign the Ukraine–European Union Association Agreement.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Yanukovych won the 2010 presidential election with strong support from voters in the Autonomous Republic of Crimea and southern and eastern Ukraine.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The Crimean autonomous government strongly supported Yanukovych and condemned the protests, saying they were "threatening political stability in the country".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The Crimean autonomous parliament said that it supported the government's decision to suspend negotiations on the pending association agreement and urged Crimeans to "strengthen friendly ties with Russian regions".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 4 February 2014, the Presidium of the Supreme Council "promised" to consider holding a referendum on the peninsula's status.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Speaker Vladimir Klychnikov asked to appeal to the Russian government to "guarantee the preservation of Crimean autonomy".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The Security Service of Ukraine (SBU) responded by opening a criminal case to investigate the possible "subversion" of Ukraine's territorial integrity.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 20 February 2014, during a visit to Moscow, Chairman of the Supreme Council of Crimea Vladimir Konstantinov stated that the 1954 transfer of Crimea from the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic to the Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic had been a mistake.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The Euromaidan protests came to a head in late February 2014, and Yanukovych and many of his ministers fled the capital on 22 February.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] After his flight, opposition parties and defectors from the Party of Regions put together a parliamentary quorum in the Verkhovna Rada (the Ukrainian parliament), and voted on 22 February to remove Yanukovych from his post on the grounds that he was unable to fulfill his duties.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Arseniy Yatsenyuk was appointed by the Rada to serve as the head of a caretaker government until new presidential and parliament elections could be held.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] This new government was recognised internationally.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] At the end of January 2014, Russian oligarch Konstantin Malofeev travelled to Crimea with his head of security, former Federal Security Service (FSB) officer Igor Girkin (alias 'Strelkov').
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Malofeev met with Vladimir Konstantinov, Chairman of the Supreme Council, asking him whether he would be willing to take "more drastic measures" to enforce Crimea's autonomy should there be a revolution.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Konstantinov had already met with Nikolai Patrushev, head of the Security Council of Russia, in Moscow in December 2013 where he told Patrushev that if Yanukovych was overthrown, Crimea would be ready to break off and become part of Russia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] At the end of January 2014, Konstantinov met with Vladislav Surkov, Putin's adviser on Ukraine.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On February 4, Konstantinov appealed to Putin to guard Crimean autonomy and began preparing a "survey" of Crimeans on what its status should be.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Surkov visited Crimea on February 14, where he might have tried to recruit Crimean prime minister, Anatolii Mohyliov, for the Russian cause.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In early February 2014, before the Ukrainian revolution, the Kremlin received a strategy paper outlining plans for the annexation of Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] It was reportedly part-written by Malofeev, and was published a year later by the Russian newspaper *Novaya Gazeta*.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The documents said that the Ukrainian government and president Viktor Yanukovych were "totally bankrupt" and would not last.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] They proposed that Russia should foster separatism in Crimea and other eastern provinces, and should begin work on taking control of them.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The documents outlined plans for starting pro-Russian protests and a public relations campaign to justify a Russian takeover.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 21 February 2014, Ukrainian president Yanukovych secretly fled the capital.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Russia's leadership worried that its naval base in Crimea might be at risk under a new Ukrainian government that was committed to closer ties with the West.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 22–23 February 2014, Russian president Putin held an all-night meeting with security chiefs to discuss the crisis.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] At the end of that meeting, Putin said: "we must start working on returning Crimea to Russia".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The GRU and FSB then began organizing sympathizers in Crimea to ensure that when the operation began there would be armed "local self‑defense groups" on the streets for support.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In January 2014, the city council of Sevastopol—home of Russia's naval base in Crimea—had called for the formation of "people's militia" units to "ensure firm defence" of the city from "extremism".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] According to political scientist Daniel Treisman, Putin may have begun planning to take Crimea even before Yanukovych was ousted.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] A source close to the commander of the operation said that Russian special forces in the port of Novorossiysk and the Black Sea Fleet in Sevastopol had already been put on alert on February 18.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Participants in the operation were later awarded a medal "For the Return of Crimea", which is engraved with February 20 as the start date of the operation.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The February 2014 Revolution of Dignity that ousted Ukrainian president Viktor Yanukovych sparked a political crisis in Crimea, which initially manifested as demonstrations against the new interim Ukrainian government, but rapidly escalated.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In late February, thousands of Russian soldiers dressed as civilians joined the "Crimean self-defense" units, as did almost one thousand Kuban Cossacks from the North Caucasus.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The activities of these groups were closely coordinated with Russian military forces and planned by Russian defense officials.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Igor Girkin ('Strelkov') oversaw command of some of the units and their coordination with Russian security officials.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Almost ten thousand people joined these "self-defense" units, but it is unclear how many were locals.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On February 20 several buses with Crimean license plates were stopped at a pro-Maidan checkpoint in a town in Cherkasy oblast.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Their passengers were violently intimidated and some buses were burned.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] This incident was subsequently used by Russian propaganda which made unsubstantiated claims that the passengers were killed in gruesome ways.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The local parliament of Crimea was the Verkhovna Rada of Crimea or Supreme Council of Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Some MPs called for an extraordinary meeting on 21 February.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In response to Russian separatist sentiment, the Security Service of Ukraine (SBU) said that it would "use severe measures to prevent any action taken against diminishing the territorial integrity and sovereignty of Ukraine".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Crimean prime minister Anatolii Mohyliov said that his government recognised the new provisional government in Kyiv, and that the Crimean autonomous government would carry out all laws passed by the Ukrainian parliament.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Meanwhile, in Sevastopol, thousands protested against the new Ukrainian government, voted to establish a parallel administration, and created civil defence squads with the support of the Russian Night Wolves motorcycle club.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Protesters waved Russian flags, chanted "Putin is our president!" and said they would refuse to further pay taxes to the Ukrainian state.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Russian military convoys were also alleged to be seen in the area.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In Kerch, pro-Russian protesters attempted to remove the Ukrainian flag from atop city hall and replace it with the flag of Russia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Over 200 attended, waving Russian, orange-and-black St.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] George, and the Russian Unity party flags.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Mayor Oleh Osadchy attempted to disperse the crowd and police eventually arrived to defend the flag.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The mayor said "This is the territory of Ukraine, Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Here's a flag of Crimea," but was accused of treason and a fight ensued over the flagpole.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 24 February, more rallied outside the Sevastopol city state administration.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Pro-Russian demonstrators accompanied by neo-Cossacks demanded the election of a Russian citizen as mayor and hoisted Russian flags around the city administration; they also handed out leaflets to sign up for a self-defence militia, warning that the "Blue-Brown Europlague is knocking".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Consequently, Sevastopol City Council illegally elected Alexei Chaly, a Russian citizen, as mayor.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Under the law of Ukraine, it was not possible for Sevastopol to elect a mayor, as the *Chairman of the Sevastopol City State Administration*, appointed by the president of Ukraine, functions as its mayor.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] A thousand protesters present chanted "A Russian mayor for a Russian city".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 25 February, several hundred pro-Russian protesters blocked the Crimean parliament demanding non-recognition of the central government of Ukraine and a referendum on Crimea's status.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On the same day, crowds gathered again outside Sevastopol's city hall on Tuesday as rumours spread that security forces could arrest Chaly, but police chief Alexander Goncharov said that his officers would refuse to carry out "criminal orders" issued by Kyiv.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Viktor Neganov, a Sevastopol-based adviser to the Internal Affairs Minister, condemned the events in the city as a coup.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] "Chaly represents the interests of the Kremlin which likely gave its tacit approval," he said.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Sevastopol City State Administration chairman Vladimir Yatsuba was booed and heckled on 23 February, when he told a pro-Russian rally that Crimea was part of Ukraine.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In Simferopol, the Regional State Administration building was blockaded with hundreds of protesters, including neo-Cossacks, demanding a referendum of separation; the rally was organized by the *Crimean Front*.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 26 February, outside the Crimean parliament building in Simferopol, 4,000–5,000 Crimean Tatars and supporters of the Euromaidan-Crimea movement faced 600–700 supporters of pro-Russian organizations and the Russian Unity Party.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Tatars leaders organised the demonstration in order to block the sitting of the Crimean parliament which is "doing everything to execute plans of separation of Crimea from Ukraine".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Supreme Council Chairman Vladimir Konstantinov said that the Crimean parliament would not consider separation from Ukraine, and that earlier reports that parliament would hold a debate on the matter were provocations.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Tatars created self-defence groups, encouraged collaboration with Russians, Ukrainians, and people of other nationalities, and called for the protection of churches, mosques, synagogues, and other important sites.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] By nightfall the Crimean Tatars had left; several hundred Russian Unity supporters rallied on.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] New Security Service of Ukraine (SBU) chief Valentyn Nalyvaichenko requested that the United Nations provide around-the-clock monitoring of the security situation in Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Russia took advantage of the uncertainty in Ukraine immediately after the ousting of Yanukovych.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 26 February, Russian soldiers without insignia began to occupy Crimea and to blockade Ukrainian military bases.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In Simferopol, the Russian soldiers seized the Crimean parliament building and the Council of Ministers building.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Russian flags were raised over these buildings and barricades were erected outside them.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] A military checkpoint, with a Russian flag and Russian military vehicles, was set up on the main highway between Sevastopol and Simferopol.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] While the armed soldiers occupied the Crimean parliament building, the parliament held an emergency session.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] It voted to dismiss the Crimean government, and replace Prime Minister Anatolii Mohyliov with Sergey Aksyonov.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Aksyonov belonged to the Russian Unity party, which received only 4% of votes in the last election.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] According to the Constitution of Ukraine, the prime minister of Crimea is appointed by the Crimean parliament (Supreme Council of Crimea) in consultation with the president of Ukraine.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Both Aksyonov and speaker Vladimir Konstantinov stated that they viewed Viktor Yanukovych as the *de jure* president of Ukraine, through whom they were able to ask Russia for help.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The parliament also voted to hold a referendum on greater autonomy, set for 25 May.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Historian Andrew Wilson and journalist Luke Harding called this the "Crimean coup".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The troops had cut all of the building's communications, and took MPs' phones as they entered.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] No independent journalists were allowed inside the building while the votes were held.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Some MPs said they were threatened and that votes were cast for them and other MPs, even though they were not in the chamber.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Interfax-Ukraine reported that there was no way to know how many MPs were present, and whether they voted themselves or if someone else used their voting cards.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The head of parliament's information and analysis department, Olha Sulnikova, phoned journalists from inside the building, telling them 61 of the registered 64 deputies had voted for the referendum resolution and 55 for the resolution to dismiss the government.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] These votes were immediately declared illegal by the Ukrainian interim government.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Russian FSB colonel Igor Girkin (alias 'Strelkov'), one of the commanders of the soldiers, said in January 2015 that Crimean MPs were held at gunpoint, and were forced to support the annexation.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The same day, more unmarked troops set up security checkpoints on the Isthmus of Perekop and the Chonhar Peninsula, which separate Crimea from the Ukrainian mainland.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] They were helped by what appeared to be local *Berkut* riot police, as well as Russian troops from the 31st Separate Airborne Assault Brigade dressed in Berkut uniforms.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Within hours, Ukraine had been cut off from Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Ukrainian TV channels became unavailable for Crimean viewers, some replaced with Russian stations.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 29 February, unmarked Russian special forces occupied Crimea's airports and communications centers.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On the day of the invasion, the Russian government dismissed accusations that it was in violation of the agreement on the Black Sea Fleet: "All movements of armored vehicles are undertaken in full compliance with the basic agreements and did not require any approvals".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 28 February, an estimated 1,400 Spetsnaz troops were flown in to the Gvardeyskoye air base from Russia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On the same day, Putin assured German Chancellor Angela Merkel in a phone call that no regular Russian soldiers are active in Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 1 March 2014, Aksyonov asked Putin for "assistance in ensuring peace and tranquillity" in Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Putin promptly received authorisation from the Federation Council of Russia for a Russian military intervention in Ukraine until the "political-social situation in the country is normalized".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Ukraine's prime minister, Arseniy Yatsenyuk, said that Russian military intervention would be the beginning of war, and Ukraine's representative told an emergency meeting of the UN Security Council that Russia was committing "an act of aggression against the state of Ukraine".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] By 2 March, Russian troops were in full control of Crimea, having deployed from the naval base in Sevastopol and reinforced by troops, armour, and helicopters from mainland Russia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] At a press conference on 4 March, president Putin said that Russia had no plans to annex Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] He also said that it had no plans to invade Ukraine, but that it might intervene if Russians in Ukraine were threatened.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Numerous media reports and statements by the Ukrainian and foreign governments noted the identity of the unmarked troops as Russian soldiers, but Russian officials concealed the identity of their forces, claiming they were local "self-defence" units over whom they had no authority.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] As late as 17 April, Russian foreign minister Sergey Lavrov said that there were no "excessive Russian troops" in Ukraine, referring to those who were allowed to be at the Sevastopol naval base.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Putin later acknowledged that he had ordered "work to bring Crimea back into Russia" as early as February.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Russia eventually admitted its troops' presence.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Defence Minister Sergey Shoygu said Russian military actions in Crimea were undertaken by forces of the Black Sea Fleet and were justified by a "threat to lives of Crimean civilians" and danger of "takeover of Russian military infrastructure by extremists".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Ukraine complained that Russia violated the agreement under which it headquartered its Black Sea Fleet in Sevastopol and violated the country's sovereignty.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The United States and United Kingdom accused Russia of breaking the terms of the Budapest Memorandum on Security Assurances, by which Russia, the US, and the UK had affirmed they would not use force against the territorial integrity or political independence of Ukraine.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The Russian government said the Budapest Memorandum did not apply due to "circumstances resulting from the action of internal political or socio-economic factors".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In March 2015, retired Russian Admiral Igor Kasatonov said that, according to his information, the Russian troop deployment in Crimea included six helicopter landings and three landings of an IL-76 with 500 troops.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The obligations between Russia and Ukraine with regard to territorial integrity and the prohibition of the use of force are laid down in a number of multilateral or bilateral agreements to which Russia and Ukraine are signatories.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Vladimir Putin said that Russian troops in the Crimean Peninsula were aimed "to ensure proper conditions for the people of Crimea to be able to freely express their will," whilst Ukraine and other nations argue that such intervention is a violation of Ukraine's sovereignty.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In the 1994 Budapest Memorandum on Security Assurances Russia was among those who affirmed to respect the territorial integrity of Ukraine (including Crimea) and to refrain from the threat or use of force against the territorial integrity or political independence of Ukraine.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] According to Ukraine usage of navigation stations and troop movements were improperly covered by the treaty and were violated many times as well as related court decisions.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] February's troop movements were in "complete disregard" of the treaty.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] According to the Constitution of Russia, the admission of new federal subjects is governed by federal constitutional law (art.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 28 February 2014, Russian MP Sergey Mironov, along with other members of the Duma, introduced a bill to alter Russia's procedure for adding federal subjects.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The declaration directly referred to the Kosovo independence precedent, by which the Albanian-populated Autonomous Province of Kosovo and Metohija declared independence from Russia's ally Serbia as the Republic of Kosovo in 2008—a unilateral action Russia staunchly opposed.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Crimean authorities' stated plans to declare independence from Ukraine made the Mironov bill unnecessary.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 20 March 2014, two days after the treaty of accession was signed, the bill was withdrawn by its initiators.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The referendum date was later moved from 25 May to 30 March.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] A Ukrainian court declared the referendum to be illegal.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 6 March, the Supreme Council moved the referendum date to 16 March and changed its scope to ask a new question: whether Crimea should apply to join Russia as a federal subject or restore the 1992 Crimean constitution within Ukraine, which the Ukrainian government had previously invalidated.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] This referendum, unlike one announced earlier, contained no option to maintain the *status quo* of governance under the 1998 constitution.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Ukraine's acting president, Oleksandr Turchynov, stated that "The authorities in Crimea are totally illegitimate, both the parliament and the government.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] They are forced to work under the barrel of a gun and all their decisions are dictated by fear and are illegal".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 14 March, the Crimean status referendum was deemed unconstitutional by the Constitutional Court of Ukraine, and a day later, the Verkhovna Rada formally dissolved the Crimean parliament.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] With a referendum looming, Russia massed troops near the Ukrainian eastern border, likely to threaten escalation and stymie Ukraine's response.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The referendum was held despite the opposition from the Ukrainian government.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Official results reported about 95.5% of participating voters in Crimea (turnout was 83%) were in favour of seceding from Ukraine and joining Russia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Crimean Tatars mostly boycotted the referendum.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] According to a survey carried out by Pew Research Center in 2014, 54% of Crimean residents supported the right of regions to secede, 91% believed the referendum was free and fair and 88% believed that the government in Kyiv ought to recognize the results of the vote.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The means by which the referendum was conducted were widely criticised by foreign governments and in the Ukrainian and international press, with reports that anyone holding a Russian passport regardless of residency in Crimea was allowed to vote.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] OSCE refused to send observers to the referendum, stating that invitation should have come from an OSCE member state in question (i.e.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Ukraine), rather than local authorities.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Russia invited a group of observers from various European far-right political parties aligned with Putin, who stated the referendum was conducted in a free and fair manner.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The **Republic of Crimea** was short lived.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The Crimean parliament declared the "partial repeal" of Ukrainian laws and began nationalising private and Ukrainian state property located on the Crimean Peninsula, including Ukrainian ports and property of Chornomornaftogaz.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Parliament also formally requested that the Russian government admit the breakaway republic into Russia, with Sevastopol asking to be admitted as a "city of federal significance".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On the same day, the *de facto* Supreme Council renamed itself the State Council of Crimea, declared the Russian ruble an official currency alongside the hryvnia, and in June the Russian ruble became the only form of legal tender.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Putin officially recognised the Republic of Crimea 'as a sovereign and independent state' by decree on 17 March.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 21 March the Republic of Crimea became a federal Subject of Russia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 19 March, the Russian Constitutional Court decided that the treaty is in compliance with the Constitution of Russia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The treaty was ratified by the Federal Assembly and Federation Council by 21 March.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] A Just Russia's Ilya Ponomarev was the only State Duma member to vote against the treaty.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The Republic of Crimea and the federal city of Sevastopol became the 84th and 85th federal subjects of Russia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] During a controversial incident in Simferopol on 18 March, some Ukrainian sources said that armed gunmen that were reported to be Russian special forces allegedly stormed the base.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] This was contested by Russian authorities, who subsequently announced the arrest of an alleged Ukrainian sniper in connection with the killings, but later denied the arrest had occurred.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The two casualties had a joint funeral attended by both the Crimean and Ukrainian authorities, and both the Ukrainian soldier and Russian paramilitary "self-defence volunteer" were mourned together.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] As of March 2014 the incident was under investigation by both the Crimean authorities and the Ukrainian military.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In response to shooting, Ukraine's then acting defense minister Ihor Tenyukh authorised Ukrainian troops stationed in Crimea to use deadly force in life-threatening situations.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] This increased the risk of bloodshed during any takeover of Ukrainian military installations, yet the ensuing Russian operations to seize the remaining Ukrainian military bases and ships in Crimea did not bring new fatalities, although weapons were used and several people were injured.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] The Russian units involved in such operations were ordered to avoid usage of deadly force when possible.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Morale among the Ukrainian troops, which for three weeks were blockaded inside their compounds without any assistance from the Ukrainian government, was very low, and the vast majority of them did not offer any real resistance.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 24 March, the Ukrainian government ordered the full withdrawal of all of its armed forces from Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Approximately 50% of the Ukrainian soldiers in Crimea had defected to the Russian military.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 26 March the last Ukrainian military bases and Ukrainian Navy ships were captured by Russian troops.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 27 March, the United Nations General Assembly adopted a non-binding resolution, which declared the Crimean referendum and subsequent status change invalid, by a vote of 100 to 11, with 58 abstentions and 24 absent.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Crimea and Sevastopol switched to Moscow Time at 10 p.m. on 29 March.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 31 March, Russia unilaterally denounced the Kharkiv Pact and Partition Treaty on the Status and Conditions of the Black Sea Fleet.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Putin cited "the accession of the Republic of Crimea and Sevastopol into Russia" and resulting "practical end of renting relationships" as his reason for the denunciation.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On the same day, he signed a decree formally rehabilitating the Crimean Tatars, who were ousted from their lands in 1944, and the Armenian, German, Greek, and Bulgarian minority communities in the region that Stalin also ordered removed in the 1940s.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Also on 31 March 2014, the Russian prime minister Dmitry Medvedev announced a series of programmes aimed at swiftly incorporating the territory of Crimea into Russia's economy and infrastructure.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Medvedev announced the creation of a new ministry for Crimean affairs, and ordered Russia's top ministers who joined him there to make coming up with a development plan their top priority.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 3 April 2014, the Republic of Crimea and the city of Sevastopol became parts of Russia's Southern Military District.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 7 May 2015, Crimea switched its phone code system from the Ukrainian number system to the Russian number system.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 11 April, the Constitution of the Republic of Crimea and City Charter of Sevastopol were adopted by their respective legislatures, coming into effect the following day in addition the new federal subjects were enumerated in a newly published revision of the Russian Constitution.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Russia withdrew its forces from southern Kherson in December 2014.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In December 2014, and electricity supply agreement was made between Ukraine's Ukrinterenergo and Russia's Inter RAO that electricity would be supplied from Ukraine in return for an equivalent supply of Russian electricity to Ukraine, which resolved electricity rationing in Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In July 2015, Russian prime minister, Dmitry Medvedev, declared that Crimea had been fully integrated into Russia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Until 2016 these new subjects were grouped in the Crimean Federal District.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In 2017, a survey performed by the Centre for East European and International Studies showed that 85% of the non-Crimean Tatar respondents believed that if the referendum would be held again it would lead to the same or "only marginally different" results.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] Crimea was fully integrated into the Russian media sphere, and links with the rest of Ukraine were hardly existent.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] On 28 December 2018, Russia completed a high-tech security fence marking the de facto border between Crimea and Ukraine.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p01] In 2021, Ukraine launched the Crimea Platform, a diplomatic initiative aimed at protecting the rights of Crimean inhabitants and ultimately reversing the annexation of Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Initially after the annexation, salaries rose, especially those of government workers.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] This was soon offset by the increase in prices caused by the depreciation of the ruble.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Wages were cut back by 30% to 70% after Russian authority became established.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Tourism, previously Crimea's main industry, suffered in particular, down by 50% from 2014 in 2015.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Crimean agricultural yields were also significantly impacted by the annexation.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Ukraine cut off supplies of water through the North Crimean Canal, which supplies 85% of Crimea's fresh water, causing the 2014 rice crop to fail, and greatly damaging the maize and soybean crops.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The annexation had a negative influence on Russians working in Ukraine and Ukrainians working in Russia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The number of tourists visiting Crimea in the 2014 season was lower than in the previous years due to a combination of "Western sanctions", ethical objections by Ukrainians, and the difficulty of getting there for Russians.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The Russian government attempted to stimulate the flow of tourists by subsidizing holidays in the peninsula for children and state workers from all Russia which worked mostly for state-owned hotels.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In 2015, overall 3 million tourists visited Crimea according to official data, while before annexation it was around 5.5 million on average.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The shortage is attributed mostly to stopped flow of tourists from Ukraine.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Hotels and restaurants are also experiencing problems with finding enough seasonal workers, who were most arriving from Ukraine in the preceding years.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Tourists visiting state-owned hotels were complaining mostly about low standard of rooms and facilities, some of them still unrepaired from Soviet times.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] According to the German newspaper *Die Welt*, the annexation of Crimea is economically disadvantageous for the Russian Federation.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Russia will have to spend billions of euros a year to pay salaries and pensions.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Moreover, Russia will have to undertake costly projects to connect Crimea to the Russian water supply and power system because Crimea has no land connection to Russia and at present (2014) gets water, gas and electricity from mainland Ukraine.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] This required building a bridge and a pipeline across the Kerch Strait.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Also, Novinite claims that a Ukrainian expert told *Die Welt* that Crimea "will not be able to attract tourists".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The then first Deputy to Minister of Finance of Russian Federation Tatyana Nesterenko said that the decision to annex Crimea was made by Vladimir Putin exclusively, without consulting Russia's Finance Ministry.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The Russian business newspaper *Kommersant* expresses an opinion that Russia will not acquire anything economically from "accessing" Crimea, which is not very developed industrially, having just a few big factories, and whose yearly gross product is only $4 billion.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The newspaper also says that everything from Russia will have to be delivered by sea, higher costs of transportation will result in higher prices for everything, and to avoid a decline in living standards Russia will have to subsidise Crimean people for a few months.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In total, Kommersant estimates the costs of integrating Crimea into Russia in $30 billion over the next decade, i.e. $3 billion per year.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Western oil expertsestimate that Russia's seizing of Crimea, and the associated control of an area of Black Sea more than three times its land area gives it access to oil and gas reserves potentially worth trillions of dollars.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] It also deprives Ukraine of its chances of energy independence.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Moscow's acquisition may alter the route along which the South Stream pipeline would be built, saving Russia money, time and engineering challenges.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] It would also allow Russia to avoid building in Turkish territorial waters, which was necessary in the original route to avoid Ukrainian territory.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] This pipeline was later canceled in favour of TurkStream, however.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The Russian Federal Service for Communications (Roskomnadzor) warned about a transition period as Russian operators have to change the numbering capacity and subscribers.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Country code will be replaced from the Ukrainian +380 to Russian +7.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Codes in Crimea start with 65, but in the area of "7" the 6 is given to Kazakhstan which shares former Soviet Union +7 with Russia, so city codes have to change.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The regulator assigned 869 dialling code to Sevastopol and the rest of the peninsula received a 365 code.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] At the time of the unification with Russia, telephone operators and Internet service providers in Crimea and Sevastopol are connected to the outside world through the territory of Ukraine.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Minister of Communications of Russia, Nikolai Nikiforov announced on his Twitter account that postal codes in Crimea will now have six-figures: to the existing five-digit number the number two will be added at the beginning.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] For example, the Simferopol postal code 95000 will become 295000.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In the area that now forms the border between Crimea and Ukraine mining the salt lake inlets from the sea that constitute the natural borders, and in the spit of land left over stretches of no-man's-land with wire on either side was created.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On early June that year Prime Minister Dmitry Medvedev signed a Government resolution No.961 dated 5 June 2014 establishing air, sea, road and railway checkpoints.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The adopted decisions create a legal basis for the functioning of a checkpoint system at the Russian state border in the Republic of Crimea and Sevastopol.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In the year following the annexation, armed men seized various Crimean businesses, including banks, hotels, shipyards, farms, gas stations, a bakery, a dairy, and Yalta Film Studio.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Russian media have noted this trend as "returning to the 90's," which is perceived as a period of anarchy and rule of gangs in Russia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] After 2014 the Russian government invested heavily in the peninsula's infrastructure—repairing roads, modernizing hospitals and building the Crimean Bridge that links the peninsula to the Russian mainland.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Development of new sources of water was undertaken, with huge difficulties, to replace closed Ukrainian sources.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In 2015, the Investigative Committee of Russia announced a number of theft and corruption cases in infrastructure projects in Crimea, for example; spending that exceeded the actual accounted costs by a factor of three.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] A number of Russian officials were also arrested for corruption, including head of federal tax inspection.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] (According to February 2016 official Ukrainian figures) after Russia's annexation 10% of Security Service of Ukraine personnel left Crimea; accompanied by 6,000 of the pre-annexation 20,300 people strong Ukrainian army.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] As result of the disputed political status of Crimea, Russian mobile operators never expanded their operations into Crimea and all mobile services are offered on the basis of "internal roaming," which caused significant controversy inside Russia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Telecoms however argued that expanding coverage to Crimea will put them at risk of Western sanctions and, as result, they will lose access to key equipment and software, none of which is produced locally.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The first five years of Crimean occupation cost Russia over $20 billion, roughly equal to two years of Russia's entire education budget.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] According to the United Nations and multiple NGOs, Russia is responsible for multiple human rights abuses, including torture, arbitrary detention, forced disappearances and instances of discrimination, including persecution of Crimean Tatars in Crimea since the illegal annexation.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The UN Human Rights Office has documented multiple human rights violations in Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Noting that minority Crimean Tatars have been disproportionately affected.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In December 2016, the UN General Assembly voted on a resolution on human rights in occupied Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] It also urged Russia to "immediately release Ukrainian citizens who were unlawfully detained and judged without regard for elementary standards of justice".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] After the annexation, Russian authorities banned Crimean Tatar organizations, filed criminal charges against Tatar leaders and journalists, and targeted the Tatar population.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The Atlantic Council have described this as the practice of collective punishment, and therefore as a war crime prohibited under international humanitarian law and Geneva convention.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In March 2014, Human Rights Watch reported that pro-Ukrainian activists and journalists had been attacked, abducted, and tortured by "self-defense" groups.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Some Crimeans were simply "disappeared" with no explanation.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 9 May 2014, the new "anti-extremist" amendment to the Criminal Code of Russia, passed in December 2013, came into force.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Article 280.1 designated incitement of violation of territorial integrity of the Russian Federation (incl. calls for secession of Crimea from Russia) as a criminal offense in Russia, punishable by a fine of 300 thousand roubles or imprisonment up to 3 years.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] If such statements are made in public media or the internet, the punishment could be obligatory works up to 480 hours or imprisonment up to five years.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The Crimean Tatar television station was also shut down by the Russian authorities.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 16 May the new Russian authorities of Crimea issued a ban on the annual commemorations of the anniversary of the deportation of the Crimean Tatars by Stalin in 1944, citing "possibility of provocation by extremists" as a reason.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Previously, when Crimea was controlled by Ukraine, these commemorations had taken place every year.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The Russian-installed Crimean authorities also banned Mustafa Dzhemilev, a human rights activist, Soviet dissident, member of the Ukrainian parliament, and former chairman of the Mejlis of the Crimean Tatars from entering Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Additionally, Mejlis reported, that officers of Russia's Federal Security Service (FSB) raided Tatar homes in the same week, on the pretense of "suspicion of terrorist activity".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The Tatar community eventually did hold commemorative rallies in defiance of the ban.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In response Russian authorities flew helicopters over the rallies in an attempt to disrupt them.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In May 2015, a local activist, Alexander Kostenko, was sentenced to four years in a penal colony.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] His lawyer, Dmitry Sotnikov, said that the case was fabricated and that his client had been beaten and starved.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Crimean prosecutor Natalia Poklonskaya accused Kostenko of making Nazi gestures during the Maidan protests, and that they were judging "not just [Kostenko], but the very idea of fascism and Nazism, which are trying to raise their head once again".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Sotnikov responded that "There are fabricated cases in Russia, but rarely such humiliation and physical harm.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] A living person is being tortured for a political idea, to be able to boast winning over fascism".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In June 2015, Razom released a report compiling human rights abuses in Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In its 2016 annual report, the Council of Europe made no mention of human rights abuses in Crimea because Russia had not allowed its monitors to enter.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In February 2016 human rights defender Emir-Usein Kuku from Crimea was arrested and accused of belonging to the Islamist organization Hizb ut-Tahrir although he denies any involvement in this organization.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Amnesty International has called for his immediate release.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 24 May 2014, Ervin Ibragimov, a former member of the Bakhchysarai Town Council and a member of the World Congress of Crimean Tatars went missing.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] CCTV footage from a camera at a nearby shop documents that Ibragimov had been stopped by a group of men and that he is briefly speaking to the men before being forced in their van.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] According to the Kharkiv Human Rights Protection Group Russian authorities refuse to investigate the disappearance of Ibragimov.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In May 2018 Server Mustafayev, the founder and coordinator of the human rights movement Crimean Solidarity was imprisoned by Russian authorities and charged with "membership of a terrorist organisation".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Amnesty International and Front Line Defenders demand his immediate release.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 12 June 2018, Ukraine lodged a memorandum weighing about 90 kg, consisting of 17,500 pages of text in 29 volumes to the UN's International Court of Justice about racial discrimination by Russian authorities in occupied Crimea and state financing of terrorism by Russian Federation in Donbas.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Between 2015 and 2019 over 134,000 people living in Crimea applied for and were issued Ukrainian passports.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Prior to Russian occupation, support for joining Russia was 23% in a 2013 poll, down from 33% in 2011.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] A joint survey by American government agency Broadcasting Board of Governors and polling firm Gallup was taken during April 2014.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The survey found that 82.8% of those polled believed that the results of the Crimean status referendum reflected the views of most residents of Crimea, whereas 6.7% said that it did not.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] 73.9% of those polled said that they thought that the annexation would have a positive impact on their lives, whereas 5.5% said that it would not.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] A comprehensive poll released on 8 May 2014 by the Pew Research Centre surveyed local opinions on the annexation.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Despite international criticism of 16 March referendum on Crimean status, 91% of those Crimeans polled thought that the vote was free and fair, and 88% said that the Ukrainian government should recognise the results.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In a survey completed in 2019 by a Russian company FOM 72% of surveyed Crimean residents said their lives have improved since annexation.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] At the same time only 39% Russians living in the mainland said the annexation was beneficial for the country as a whole which marks a significant drop from 67% in 2015.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Immediately after the treaty of accession was signed in March, the Ukrainian Ministry of Foreign Affairs summoned the Provisional Principal of Russia in Ukraine to present *note verbale* of protest against Russia's recognition of the Republic of Crimea and its subsequent annexation.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Two days later, the Verkhovna Rada condemned the treaty and called Russia's actions "a gross violation of international law".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The Rada called on the international community to avoid recognition of the "so-called Republic of Crimea" or the annexation of Crimea and Sevastopol by Russia as new federal subjects.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 15 April 2014, the Verkhovna Rada declared the Autonomous Republic of Crimea and Sevastopol to be under "provisional occupation" by the Russian military and imposed travel restrictions on Ukrainians visiting Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The territories were also deemed "inalienable parts of Ukraine" subject to Ukrainian law.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Among other things, the special law approved by the Rada restricted foreign citizens' movements to and from the Crimean Peninsula and forbade certain types of entrepreneurship.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The law also forbade activity of government bodies formed in violation of Ukrainian law and designated their acts as null and void.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Ukrainian authorities greatly reduced the volume of water flowing into Crimea via the North Crimean Canal due to huge debt for water supplied in the previous year, threatening the viability of the peninsula's agricultural crops, which are heavily dependent on irrigation.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In March 2014, activists began organising flash mobs in supermarkets to urge customers not to buy Russian goods and to boycott Russian gas stations, banks, and concerts.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In April 2014, some cinemas in Kyiv, Lviv, and Odesa began shunning Russian films.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 2 December 2014, Ukraine created a Ministry of Information Policy, with one of its goals being, according to first Minister of Information, Yuriy Stets, to counteract "Russian information aggression".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In December 2014, Ukraine halted all train and bus services to Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 16 September 2015, the Ukrainian parliament voted for the law that sets 20 February 2014 as the official date of the Russian temporary occupation of the Crimean Peninsula.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 7 October 2015, the president of Ukraine signed the law into force.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The Ministry of Temporarily Occupied Territories and IDPs was established by the Ukrainian government on 20 April 2016 to manage occupied parts of Donetsk, Luhansk and Crimea regions affected by Russian military intervention of 2014.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] By 2015, the number of IDPs registered in Ukraine who had fled from Russian-occupied Crimea was 50,000.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] We will be examining the situation and doing so fast".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] They also stated that in the event of a referendum for the Crimea region joining the Russian Federation, they would consider its results "very fast".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Later Slutsky announced that he was misunderstood by the Crimean press, and no decision regarding simplifying the process of acquiring Russian citizenship for people in Crimea had been made yet.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] He also added that if "fellow Russian citizens are in jeopardy, you understand that we do not stay away".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 25 February, in a meeting with Crimean politicians, he stated that Viktor Yanukovych was still the legitimate president of Ukraine.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] That same day, the Russian Duma announced it was determining measures so that Russians in Ukraine who "did not want to break from the Russian World" could acquire Russian citizenship.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 27 February, the Russian governing agencies presented the new law project on granting citizenship.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The Russian Ministry of Foreign Affairs called on the West and particularly NATO to "abandon the provocative statements and respect the neutral status of Ukraine".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In its statement, the ministry claims that the agreement on settlement of the crisis, which was signed on 21 February and was witnessed by foreign ministries from Germany, Poland and France had to this date, not been implemented (Vladimir Lukin from Russia had not signed it).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 28 February, according to ITAR-TASS, the Russian Ministry of Transport discontinued further talks with Ukraine in regards to the Crimean Bridge project.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] However, on 3 March Dmitry Medvedev, then Prime Minister of Russia, signed a decree creating a subsidiary of Russian Highways (Avtodor) to build a bridge at an unspecified location along the Kerch Strait.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On Russian social networks, there was a movement to gather volunteers who served in the Russian army to go to Ukraine.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Many political researchers consider that after the annexation a social period in Russia coined as "Crimean consensus" begun, during which the "Rally 'round the flag" effect was observed in the population.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 28 February, President Putin stated in telephone calls with key EU leaders that it was of "extreme importance of not allowing a further escalation of violence and the necessity of a rapid normalisation of the situation in Ukraine".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Already on 19 February the Russian Ministry of Foreign Affairs had referred to the Euromaidan revolution as the "Brown revolution".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In Moscow, on 2 March, an estimated 27,000 rallied in support of the Russian government's decision to intervene in Ukraine.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The rallies received considerable attention on Russian state TV and were officially approved by the government.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Meanwhile, on 1 March, five people who were picketing next to the Federation Council building against the invasion of Ukraine were arrested.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The next day about 200 people protested at the building of the Russian Ministry of Defence in Moscow against Russian military involvement.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] About 500 people also gathered to protest on the Manezhnaya Square in Moscow, and the same number of people on the Saint Isaac's Square in Saint Petersburg.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 2 March, about eleven protesters demonstrated in Yekaterinburg against Russian involvement, with some wrapped in the Ukrainian flag.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Protests were also held in Chelyabinsk on the same day.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Opposition to the military intervention was also expressed by rock musician Andrey Makarevich, who wrote in particular: "You want war with Ukraine?
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] It will not be the way it was with Abkhazia: the folks on the Maidan have been hardened and know what they are fighting for – for their country, their independence. ...
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] But it's up to them how they want to live".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The Professor of the Department of Philosophy at the Moscow State Institute of International Relations Andrey Zubov was fired for his article in *Vedomosti*, criticising Russian military intervention.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 2 March, one Moscow resident protested against Russian intervention by holding a "Stop the war" banner, but he was immediately harassed by passers-by.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] A woman came forward with a fabricated charge against him, of beating up a child; however, her claim, due to lack of a victim and obviously false, was ignored by the police.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Andrei Zubov, a professor at the Moscow State Institute of International Relations, who compared Russian actions in Crimea to the 1938 Annexation of Austria by Nazi Germany, was threatened.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Alexander Chuyev, the leader of the pro-Kremlin Spravedlivaya Rossiya party, also objected to Russian intervention in Ukraine.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Boris Akunin, a popular Russian writer, predicted that Russia's moves would lead to political and economic isolation.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] President Putin's approval rating among the Russian public increased by nearly 10% since the crisis began, up to 71.6%, the highest in three years, according to a poll conducted by the All-Russian Center for Public Opinion Research, released on 19 March.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Additionally, the same poll showed that more than 90% of Russians supported unification with the Crimean Republic.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 4 March, at a press conference in Novo-Ogaryovo, President Putin expressed his view on the situation that if a revolution took place in Ukraine, it would be a new country with which Russia had not concluded any treaties.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] He offered an analogy with the events of 1917 in Russia, when as a result of the revolution the Russian Empire fell apart and a new state was created.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] However, he stated Ukraine would still have to honour its debts.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Russian politicians speculated that there were already 143,000 Ukrainian refugees in Russia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The Ukrainian Ministry of Foreign Affairs refuted those claims of refugee increases in Russia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] At a briefing on 4 March 2014, the director of the department of information policy of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Ukraine Yevhen Perebyinis said that Russia was misinforming its own citizens as well as the entire international community to justify its own actions in the Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 5 March, an anchor of the Russian-controlled TV channel RT America, Abby Martin, criticized her employer's biased coverage of the military invervention.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In early March, Igor Andreyev, a 75-year-old survivor of the Siege of Leningrad, attended an anti-war rally against the Russian intervention in Crimea and was holding a sign that read "Peace to the World".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The riot police arrested him, and a local pro-government lawyer then accused him of being a supporter of "fascism".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The retiree, who lived on a 6,500-ruble monthly pension, was fined 10,000 rubles.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Prominent dissident Mikhail Khodorkovsky said that Crimea should stay within Ukraine with broader autonomy.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Tatarstan, a republic within Russia populated by Volga Tatars, has sought to alleviate concerns about the treatment of Tatars by Russia, as Tatarstan is an oil-rich and economically successful republic in Russia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 5 March, President of Tatarstan Rustam Minnikhanov signed an agreement on co-operation between Tatarstan and the Aksyonov government in Crimea that implied collaboration between ten government institutions as well as significant financial aid to Crimea from Tatarstan businesses.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 11 March, Minnikhanov was in Crimea on his second visit and attended as a guest in the Crimean parliament chamber during the vote on the declaration of sovereignty pending 16 March referendum.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The Tatarstan's Mufti Kamil Samigullin invited Crimean Tatars to study in madrasas in Kazan, and declared support for their "brothers in faith and blood".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Mustafa Dzhemilev, a former leader of the Crimean Tatar Majlis, believed that forces that were suspected to be Russian forces should leave the Crimean Peninsula, and asked the UN Security Council to send peacekeepers into the region.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 15 March, thousands of protesters (estimates varying from 3,000 by official sources up to 50,000 claimed by the opposition) in Moscow marched against Russian involvement in Ukraine, many waving Ukrainian flags.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] At the same time, a pro-government (and pro-referendum) rally occurred across the street, counting in the thousands as well (officials claiming 27,000 with the opposition claiming about 10,000).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In June 2015 Mikhail Kasyanov stated that all Russian Duma decisions on Crimea annexation were illegal from the international point of view and the annexation was provoked by false accusations of discrimination of Russian nationals in Ukraine.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] As of January 2019, Arkady Rotenberg through his Stroygazmontazh LLC and his companies building the Crimean Bridge along with Nikolai Shamalov and Yuri Kovalchuk through their Rossiya Bank have become the most important investors in Russia's development of the annexed Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] There has been a range of international reactions to the annexation.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In March 2014, the UN General Assembly passed a non-binding resolution 100 in favour, 11 against and 58 abstentions in the 193-nation assembly that declared Crimea's Moscow-backed referendum invalid.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In a move supported by the Lithuanian president, the United States government imposed sanctions against persons they deem to have violated or assisted in the violation of Ukraine's sovereignty.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The United Kingdom qualified the referendum vote in Crimea of being "farcical", "illegal" and "illegitimate".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Ukraine and other countries claim that Russia has signed a number of treaties guaranteeing Ukrainian territorial integrity.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] These include the 1991 Belavezha Accords that established the Commonwealth of Independent States, the 1975 Helsinki Accords, the 1994 Budapest Memorandum on Security Assurances and the 1997 Treaty on friendship, cooperation and partnership between the Russian Federation and Ukraine.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The European Commission decided on 11 March 2014 to enter into a full free-trade agreement with Ukraine within the year.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 12 March, the European Parliament rejected the upcoming referendum on independence in Crimea, which they saw as manipulated and contrary to international and Ukrainian law.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The G7 bloc of developed nations (the G8 minus Russia) made a joint statement condemning Russia and announced that they would suspend preparations for the planned G8 summit in Sochi in June.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] NATO condemned Russia's military escalation in Crimea and stated that it was a breach of international law while the Council of Europe expressed its full support for the territorial integrity and national unity of Ukraine.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The Visegrád Group has issued a joint statement urging Russia to respect Ukraine's territorial integrity and for Ukraine to take into account its minority groups to not further break fragile relations.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] It has urged for Russia to respect Ukrainian and international law and in line with the provisions of the 1994 Budapest Memorandum.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] China said "We respect the independence, sovereignty and territorial integrity of Ukraine".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] A spokesman restated China's belief of non-interference in the internal affairs of other nations and urged dialogue.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The Indian government called for a peaceful resolution of the situation.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Both Syria and Venezuela openly supported Russian military action.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Syrian president Bashar al-Assad said that he supports Putin's efforts to "restore security and stability in the friendly country of Ukraine", while Venezuelan President Nicolás Maduro condemned Ukraine's "ultra-nationalist" coup.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Sri Lanka described Yanukovych's removal as unconstitutional and considered Russia's concerns in Crimea as justified.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Polish prime minister Donald Tusk called for a change in EU energy policy as Germany's dependence on Russian gas poses risks for Europe.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 13 March 2014, German Chancellor Angela Merkel warned the Russian government it risks massive damage to Russia, economically and politically, if it refuses to change course on Ukraine, though close economic links between Germany and Russia significantly reduce the scope for any sanctions.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] After Russia moved to formally incorporate Crimea, some worried whether it may do the same in other regions.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] US deputy national security advisor Tony Blinken said that the Russian troops massed on the eastern Ukrainian border may be preparing to enter the country's eastern regions.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Russian officials stated that Russian troops would not enter other areas.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Breedlove, NATO's supreme allied commander in Europe, warned that the same troops were in a position to take over the separatist Russian-speaking Moldovan province of Transnistria.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] President of Moldova Nicolae Timofti warned Russia with not attempting to do this to avoid damaging its international status further.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 9 April, the Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe deprived Russia of voting rights.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 14 August, while visiting Crimea, Vladimir Putin ruled out pushing beyond Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] He undertook to do everything he could to end the conflict in Ukraine, saying Russia needed to build calmly and with dignity, not by confrontation and war which isolated it from the rest of the world.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] vote on a draft resolution condemning the 2014 Crimean referendum.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] UN General Assembly vote on the resolution condemning the 2014 Crimean referendum.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 15 March 2014, a US-sponsored resolution that went to a vote in the UN Security Council to reaffirm that council's commitment to Ukraine's "sovereignty, independence, unity and territorial integrity" was not approved.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Though a total of 13 council members voted in favour of the resolution and China abstained, Russia vetoed the resolution.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 27 March 2014, the UN General Assembly approved a resolution describing the referendum leading to annexation of Crimea by Russia as illegal.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The draft resolution, which was titled "Territorial integrity of Ukraine", was co-sponsored by Canada, Costa Rica, Germany, Lithuania, Poland, Ukraine and the US.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] It affirmed the council's commitment to the "sovereignty, political independence, unity and territorial integrity of Ukraine within its internationally recognised borders".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The resolution tried to underscore that 16 March referendum held in Crimea and the city of Sevastopol has no validity and cannot form the basis for any alteration of the status of the Autonomous Republic of Crimea or of the city of Sevastopol.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The resolution got 100 votes in its favour, while 11 nations voted against and 58 countries abstained from the vote.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The resolution was non-binding and the vote was largely symbolic.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Since 2014, the UN General Assembly has voted several times, most recently in December 2019, to affirm Ukraine's territorial integrity, condemn the 'temporary occupation' of Crimea, and reaffirm nonrecognition of its annexation.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Afghanistan, Cuba, North Korea, Kyrgyzstan, Nicaragua, Sudan, Syria, and Zimbabwe have recognised the result of the 2014 referendum in Crimea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Four non-UN member states recognised the results of the referendum: Abkhazia, South Ossetia, Artsakh and Transnistria.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The Transnistrian foreign minister, Nina Shtanski, recognized Crimea's annexation by Russia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Transnistria sent a request on 18 March 2014 to join the Russian Federation following the Crimean example and in compliance with the Admission Law provisions.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The regional councils of Italy's northern regions Lombardy, Liguria and Veneto adopted a non-binding resolution on recognizing Crimea as part of Russia, but they revoked it in 2022 after Russia invaded Ukraine.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Sanctions were imposed to prevent officials and politicians from travelling to Canada, the United States, or the European Union.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] They were the most wide-ranging applied to Russia since the fall of the Soviet Union.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Japan announced milder sanctions than the US and EU.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] These include suspension of talks relating to military, space, investment, and visa requirements.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In response to the sanctions introduced by the US and EU, the Russian Duma unanimously passed a resolution asking for all members of the Duma to be included on the sanctions list.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Head of the Just Russia party Sergei Mironov said he was proud of being included on the sanctions list: "It is with pride that I have found myself on the black list, this means they have noticed my stance on Crimea".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Russian companies started pulling billions of dollars out of Western banks to avoid having their asset frozen.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Three days after the lists were published, the Russian Foreign Ministry published a reciprocal sanctions list of US citizens, which consisted of 10 names, including House Speaker John Boehner, Senator John McCain, and two advisers to President Obama.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The ministry said in a statement: "We have repeatedly warned that sanctions are a double-edged instrument and would hit the United States like a boomerang".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Several of those sanctioned responded with pride at their inclusion on the list, including John Boehner, John McCain, Bob Menendez, Dan Coats, Mary Landrieu, and Harry Reid.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] On 24 March, Russia imposed retaliatory sanctions on 13 Canadian officials including members of the Parliament of Canada, banning them from entering Russia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Foreign Affairs Minister John Baird, said the sanctions were "a badge of honour".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Former Minister of Justice Irwin Cotler also said that he considered the sanctions a badge of honour, not a mark of exclusion.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] "The good news is that so far, Russia has shown no inclination to use the Northern Distribution Network as leverage in the wake of US retaliation for its troop movements in Crimea".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Expanded Western sanctions in mid-March coursed through financial markets, hitting the business interests of some of Russia's richest people.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The Americans centred on the heart of Moscow's leadership, though the EU's initial list shied from targeting Putin's inner circle.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Novatek, Russia's second-largest gas producer, saw $2.5bn in market value wiped out when its shares sank by nearly 10%, rendering Putin's close friend Gennady Timchenko, who has a 23% stake in the company, $575m poorer.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] "I do hope that there is some serious diplomatic activity going on behind the scenes," said one Russian banker, though others were more sanguine on the question of whether the sanctions would have any enduring effect, and Russians, top and bottom, seemed defiant.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] The official Russian response was mixed.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] As well as differences between the United States and Europe as a whole as to how to respond to the Russian-backed incursion, those same differences have played out among Eastern European countries.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] A number of Russian citizens reported that they have been denied European visas after they visited Crimea after annexation.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In response to having its voting rights revoked, Russia in June 2017 suspended its budget payments to the Council of Europe, with Russian foreign minister Sergei Lavrov stating payments would not resume until all rights of Russia's delegation were fully restored.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Council Secretary General Thorbjørn Jagland has suggested lifting the sanctions to avoid the impact of mounting budgetary restraints.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] However, Council members such as Ukraine and its supporters have argued that readmitting Russia without demanding concessions in return would amount to "caving to Russian 'blackmail'".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] Researchers consider the subsequent annexation of Crimea to be a coup, because the Russian military seized Crimea's parliament and government buildings and instigated the replacement of its government with Russian proxies.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/2014-russian-annexation-of-crimea-p02] In particular, political scientist Olga Burlyuk defines Crimea events as "a coup d'état of a regional scale".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Adamawa Fulfulde was originally brought to Cameroon in the early parts of the 19th century during a religious war (Jihad) that was launched by Usman dan Fodio from Northern Nigeria.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] It is an Atlantic language that belongs to the Niger–Congo language family.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The speakers of the language are the Fulani people.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The language itself is divided into a number of sub-dialects: Maroua, Garoua, Ngaondéré, Kambariire, Mbororoore, and Bilkire.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In Sudan, the language is spoken mainly in Blue Nile, Gedaref, and Sennar states with some communities of speakers also found in North Kordofan and South Kordofan states.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In South Sudan, it is spoken in Western Bahr el Ghazal state by Ambororo cattle herders.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In Chad, it is spoken in Lac Léré Department in the Mayo-Kebbi Ouest Region.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In Nigeria, it is spoken in Adamawa and Taraba states.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] While in Cameroon the language is widespread across the Far North and Northern regions of the country.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The word order for Adamawa Fulfulde is SOV (subject–object–verb).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Adamawa Fulfulde is mostly written in a modified Arabic script, in the tradition of Ajami script, that it shares with many other languages such as Hausa language, and many other languages in Sub-Sahara Africa.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Writing Fulfulde with Arabic script has a long tradition and old manuscripts are found in all of West Africa.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Latin alphabet is also used for writing of Adamawa.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The usage of Latin is a lot more recent, only coming to existence with the arrival of European Christian.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Still, in Cameroon, Arabic alphabet remains more popular for writing of Adamawa Fulfulde than Latin.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The Adamawa Fulfulde Ajami alphabet is the result of many decades of efforts to standardize, starting from the 1960s.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] By the 1990s, the orthography was well established.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In 1998, at the JCMWA/MICCAO conference in Ngaoundéré, Cameroon, over 100 representatives from 14 West African countries agreed that this orthography would be a good standard for writing the Fulfulde language with Arabic script.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The alphabet consists of 33 basic letters, 28 plus *hamaza* from Arabic, and 4 are new letters created for use in Fulfulde.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] 10 of the Arabic letters are only used for writing Arabic loanwords, and have no use for writing indigenous Fulfulde words.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter does come in the beginning of words as a vowel diacritic carrier for common Arabic loanwords.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Character unique to Fulfulde, not found in Arabic.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [θ] in Arabic, but as [s] in Fulfulde.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter is pronounced as [h] in Fulfulde, and is used for representing the sound [h] (except in Arabic loanwords).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The latter is only used in Arabic loanwords in Fulfulde.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [x] in Arabic, but as [h] or [x] in Fulfulde.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter has a variation of pronunciations in different local dialects.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [sˤ] in Arabic, but as [s] in Fulfulde.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [dˤ] in Arabic, but as [d] in Fulfulde.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] This is the local indigenous innovation in the Adamawa dialectical area.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [q] in Arabic, but as [k~g] in Fulfulde.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] , in which case it will not carry any diacritic.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter serves two functions, either as a consonant [w], or it lengthens vowels [o] or [u].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter serves two functions, either as a consonant [j], or it lengthens vowel [i].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Letter used for lengthening of vowel [e].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In Adamawa Fulfulde, there are 4 prenasalized consonants.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Prenasalized consonants are written as a digraph (combination of two consonants).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The first letter of the digraph representing a prenasalized consonant cannot take any diacritic, including zero-vowel diacritic *sukun* '◌ْ‎'.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Like other languages that have historically been written within what's known as the Ajami tradition, there is a full relaince on diacritics for writing vowels.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In Arabic there are only three diacritics, which represent [a] '◌َ‎', [u] [i] '◌ُ‎', and [i] '◌ِ‎'.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The general tradition is that when there are vowels that don't exist in Arabic, new diacritics are created.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In Adamawa Fulfulde these include the Quranic imāla '◌ٜ‎' for vowel [e], and a special diacritic '◌ٛ‎' for vowel [o].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Unlike Arabic orthography, or other Arabic-derived scripts, in Ajami tradition, all diacritics are written.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Even letters that don't have any vowels, are written with a *zero-vowel/sukun* '◌ْ‎' diacritic.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Vowels are lengthened by combining the diacritic with a follow-up letter, just as is the tradition in Arabic.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] These follow-up letters are written without a diacritic.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] ‎' can be part of a digraph representing prenasalized consonants.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In these instances, these two letters are written without a diacritic.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe is closely related to the Kabardian or East Circassian language; some reject the distinction between the two languages in favour of both being dialects of a unitary Circassian language, others argue they are closely related but technically distinct languages.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Despite phonological differences, Circassian languages are reciprocally intelligible, with speakers being able to communicate with varying degrees of efficiency.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] While the self-designation for both Adyghe and Kabardian language is *Adyghe*, in linguistic and administrative terms, "Adyghe" refers specifically to the language of the western tribes of Circassians, while "Kabardian" refers to the language of the two eastern tribes (Kabardians and Besleney).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Ubykh, Abkhaz and Abaza are more distantly related to Adyghe.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe is also known as West Circassian or Lower Circassian.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe belongs to the Northwest Caucasian language family.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Glottochronological studies suggest that the common Proto-Northwest Caucasian language split into the Circassian, Abkhaz, and Ubykh branches roughly 5,000 years ago.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] One of the earliest attempts to create a standard for the Adyghe language was made by Natouko Sheretluk (Natouko Efendi), a Shapsug nobleman.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] He opened a madrasa in his native village of Bogundyr and compiled an Adyghe alphabet and grammar.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Leonty Lyulye, a Russian official who lived for many years among the Shapsugs, Natukhays, and Abadzekhs on the Black Sea coast, published a "Russian-Circassian Dictionary" and a brief grammar in Odessa in 1846.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Lyulye identified three dialects of Adyghe: "Kabardian", "Besleney", and a third he called "Common Circassian" (referring to the Western coastal dialects).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] He tried to base his dictionary on this "Common" dialect.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Another pre-Soviet attempt was made by Wumar Bersey, an Abzakh.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] On March 14, 1853, he published the "Primer of the Circassian Language" (Adyghe Alphabet) in Tiflis (Tbilisi), based on the Arabic script.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] This date (March 14) is now celebrated annually as the "Day of the Adyghe Language".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The standard register of Adyghe, known as Literary Adyghe (Adyghe: Литературабз, lit.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] 'Literature language'), was created by Circassian linguist Daut Ashkhamaf based largely on the Chemguy dialect, which was chosen for its simplicity.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] However, Literary Adyghe is a constructed dialect and is distinct from the natural Chemguy dialect, as there was significant input from the dialects of other tribes who remained in the Caucasus after the Circassian exile, spesifically the Bzhedug, Shapsug, and partly Abzakh.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the 1930s, Ashkhamaf even utilized the term "Bzhedug-Temirgoy dialect" to describe the basis of the literary language.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] He argued that through the development of the literary language, these dialects were merging.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In some cases, literary dialect preferred words from other dialects over Chemguy words, such as Bzhedug "ӏэ" (hand) and "тхьэ" (god) instead of the Chemguy "ӏа" and "тхьа", as well as specific ordinal numbers and verb forms.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Thus, being supra-dialectal, literary Adyghe stands in contrast to territorial dialects and serves as the unifying literary form of the language for speakers of diverse dialects.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] There were proposals to merge Adyghe and Kabardian to create a single Circassian literary language.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Another proposal was to select one of the two to serve as the single literary language for all Circassians.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] A rejected proposal by Circassian scholars argued for recognizing Kabardian as the sole literary language for all Circassians, as it had the most speakers.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] There were attempts to create a single unified alphabet for Adyghe, Kabardian, Chechen and Karachay-Balkar; but efforts failed because the leaders of the movement were accused of being "bourgeois nationalists" and executed in 1937.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Naloev, who was involved in the creation of the Kabardian alphabet, was executed by firing squad for alleged treason; he was rehabilitated posthumously in 1957.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Bolsheviks supported the creation of separate alphabets and grammars for the "Kyakh" (Western; the modern Adyghe language) and Kabardian, despite ongoing debates on unifying them.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Thus, Adyghe and Kabardian speakers could communicate easier orally as opposed to in writing due to different graphical representations and spelling rules.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] A more moderate proposal developed by the linguist M.A.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Kumakhov aimed to unify the alphabets and orthography without forcing a complete merger of spoken Adyghe and Kabardian.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] This project proposed standardizing the representation of identical phonemes (using the same letter for the same sound where they currently differ, such as the Adyghe `жъ`vs.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The project was accepted by specialists at regional conferences in Nalchik and Maikop in 1998 and 1999.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] While the Parliament of the Kabardino-Balkarian Republic approved the project, the Parliament of the Republic of Adygea did not proceed to discuss it.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Cherkess) was a result of Soviet "ethnic engineering".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The International Circassian Association (ICA) officially stated the goal of creating a "uniform Circassian language" in its 2015 congress resolution.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] There are many books written in or translated into Adyghe. А significant milestone was the publication of the "ABC-book of the Circassian language" by Wumar Bersey in Tbilisi on March 14, 1853, a date now celebrated as the Day of the Adyghe Language and Writing.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the early 20th century, reformist movements in Baksan led to the publication of religious and ethical textbooks such as "The History of Islam" (Мыслъымэн Тхыдэ) in 1918.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] A popular Adyghe translation of the Quran was made by Koshbaye Pshimaf Iskhak Mashbash.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The New Testament and many books of the Old Testament have been published in Adyghe by the Institute for Bible Translation in Moscow.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 2020 a bilingual edition of Ecclesiastes was released in Adyghe and Kabardian.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 1908, Circassian Union and Charity Society in Istanbul began printing Adyghe language texts in the newspaper *Ghuaze.* Following this, the "*Adığe-Gazete"* (Adyghe Newspaper) was introduced in 1919.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 1920, the bulletin "Diyane" was published in Istanbul using a Latin-based Adyghe alphabet.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the Middle East, a Circassian cultural society established in 1927 in El-Quneitra, Syria, published the newspaper "Mardzh" (Voice) from 1928 to 1932.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe Maq is the main Adyghe language newspaper in Russia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] It is published in the capital of the Adyghe Republic, Maykop, five times a week.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The newspaper *"*Socialist Adygea" started in Krasnodar in 1926 and relocated to Maikop ten years later. he Adigean branch of the Union of Soviet Writers launched the literary almanac "Friendship" in Maikop in 1946.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] For younger readers, the children's magazine *"*Constellation" is published in the Adyghe language.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Other early newspapers included *Qerehetlıq* (Black People) in 1924 and *Adığe Psevuç* (Adyghe Life) in 1926.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] According to the UNESCO 2009 map entitled "UNESCO Map of the World's Languages in Danger", the status of the Adyghe language in 2009, along with all its dialects (Adyghe, Western Circassian tribes; and Kabard-Cherkess, Eastern Circassian tribes), is classified as vulnerable.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe exhibits between 50 and 60 consonants depending on the dialect.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] All dialects possess a contrast between plain and labialized glottal stops.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] A very unusual minimal contrast, and possibly unique to the Abzakh dialect of Adyghe, is a three-way contrast between plain, labialized and palatalized glottal stops (although a palatalized glottal stop is also found in Hausa and a labialized one in Tlingit).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Shapsug (Black Sea) dialect of Adyghe contains a very uncommon sound: a voiceless bidental fricative [h̪͆], which corresponds to the voiceless velar fricative [x] found in other varieties of Adyghe.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] This sound is only known to be used in the Black Sea dialect.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the Black Sea coast Adyghe dialects (e.g.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Shapsug dialect and Natukhai dialect) there exist a palatalized voiced velar stop [ɡʲ], a palatalized voiceless velar stop [kʲ] and a palatalized velar ejective [kʲʼ] that were merged with [d͡ʒ], [t͡ʃ] and [t͡ʃʼ] in most Adyghe dialects.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] For example the Shapsug words "гьанэ" [ɡʲaːna] "shirt", "кьэт" [kʲat] "chicken" and "кӏьапсэ" [kʲʼaːpsa] "rope" are pronounced in other dialects as "джанэ" [d͡ʒaːna], "чэт" [t͡ʃat] and кӏапсэ [t͡ʃʼaːpsa].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In contrast to its large inventory of consonants, Adyghe has only three phonemic vowels in a vertical vowel system.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Adyghe alphabet contains some inconsistencies between visual representation and pronunciation which can be a point of confusion for learners.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] It is tempting to read the Circassian alphabet letters phonologically, but this is not always accurate.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] These letters are not part of the official alphabet, but they may appear in books that showcase the different dialects.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] For most of its history, Adyghe was an oral language.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The folklore, particularly the Nart sagas, served as a repository for the language.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Widespread literacy in Adyghe did not exist until the modern era and literacy was limited to a few people.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] From the 6th–5th centuries BC until the first half of the 15th century, the Adyghe people used the Greek alphabet, initially introduced through ancient Greek colonies and later reinforced by the Byzantine Empire and the Christian church.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Early forms of the Cyrillic alphabet were also used during this period due to Russian influence.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] During the 13th to 15th centuries, the development of relations with the Genoese Republic led to some use of the Italian (Latin) script.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the 14th century, along with Islam, the Arabic script was adopted for Adyghe.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] It was referred to as Ajam**,** a writing system for the native language based on the Perso-Arabic script.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Since Adyghe has many more consonants than Arabic, the Ajam system required adding special diacritical marks or inventing new letters to represent sounds.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Early attempts to write Adyghe in modern Cyrillic started as early as 1829 and were followed by similar attempts.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 1853, the Adyghe educator Umar Bersey published the first "Primer of the Circassian Language" based on the Arabic script.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Over the following decades, several authors attempted to further improve the Adyghe Arabic orthography.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The most successful attempt was the alphabet created by Akhmetov Bekukh.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In this version, letters were designated for vowel sounds, and the orthography was transformed from an "Impure abjads to a true alphabet.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 1918, on the initiative of the Kuban Revolutionary Committee, a primer was published in Yekaterinodar.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] This official endorsement resulted in a literary boom in Adyghe and the publication of various newspapers, textbooks and other literature, including the *Adyghe Maq*, the main Adyghe language newspaper established in 1923.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] During the abovementioned decades, parallel with this process, the Perso-Arabic orthography had also been standardized for the sister Circassian language of Kabardian.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Although very similar in many aspects, there were minor variations, in which letters were included based on each respective phonology, and there were minor differences in presentation of a few consonants as well.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Arabic script was used until 1927, when as a part of the Soviet "Latinisation" campaign, a Latin-based alphabet was adopted.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Yakovlev and the Adyghe scholar Daud Ashkhamaf.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the late 1930s, the script was converted to Cyrillic to align with Russian.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the diaspora, a new Latin alphabet based on the Turkish alphabet was designed to better facilitate Adyghe and Kabardian education in Turkey, named the ABX alphabet.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe, like all Northwest Caucasian languages, has a basic subject–object–verb typology and is characterised by the ergative construction of sentences.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Turkey hosts the largest Circassian population, but the language lacks any legal recognition.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] However, after the collapse of the Ottoman Empire and the establishment of the modern republic, these schools were banned by the Kemalists.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Following the "Citizen, Speak Turkish!" campaign and the closure of Circassian schools, the language was confined to the home.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In educational settings, speaking Adyghe was strictly banned.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Students faced physical punishment and psychological alienation for speaking Adyghe, including during recess and outside of school grounds.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] To enforce this, teachers formed "discipline committees" made up of student informants.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Publishing in the language also faced state pressure; cultural magazines had to remove Circassian lyrics from traditional songs and publish only the musical notes to avoid government retribution.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Consequently, while the older generation retains fluency, proficiency among those under 50 is significantly diminished.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In a study, Nusret Baş (Бажь Нусрэт), the then-president of the Federation of Circassian Associations, estimated that about 5% of Circassians in Turkey (including people of Circassian descent) speak their native language fluently.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Linguistically, the Adyghe spoken in Turkey exhibits distinct features as it was not subject to the standartisation policies in the Caucasus.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] It contains archaic vocabulary lost in the Caucasus, alongside Turkish loanwords.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] While the Chemguy dialect forms the basis of the literary language in the Republic of Adygea, the majority of the diaspora in Turkey speaks the Abzakh and Shapsug dialects (as well as Kabardian), alongside smaller numbers of Bzhedug and Hatuqay speakers.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Hatuqay dialect is spoken only in Turkey.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In some cases, the physical mixing of different tribes led to dialectal convergence.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Frequent intermarriages between dialect groups led to the use of a mixed Adyghe koine or the dominance of one dialect in multi-tribal areas.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In some cases, the boundaries between dialects became blurred, resulting in a hybrid oral communication style, sometimes even including hybrids with Kabardian or Abaza.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Due to assimilation, Adyghe speakers in Turkey sometimes use Turkish terms for numbers, days of the week, months, and colors.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Significant changes occurred following Turkey's European Union accession process in the early 2000s.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The language policy was liberalized, which prompted revival efforts.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 2012, the Ministry of National Education introduced "Living Languages and Dialects" as an elective course for secondary schools, allowing Adyghe to be taught in public schools.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Classes are only opened if a set minimum number of students apply, and bureaucratic hurdles regarding application windows often hinder access to these classes.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Teachers are subject teachers with basic language skills rather than trained philologists, and they receive limited training in language pedagogy.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Educational materials are imported from Adygea and are designed for native speakers, making them difficult to adapt for diaspora students who are learning Adyghe as a second language.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] During the COVID-19 pandemic, transnational online courses were organized in collaboration with institutions in Russia, allowing students in Turkey, Jordan, and Germany to be taught by teachers directly from the Caucasus.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Düzce University has a Department of Caucasian Languages and Cultures, which offers "Circassian Language and Culture" programs, including the teaching of Adyghe in Cyrillic, as the surrounding region is inhabited largely by Shapsug and Abzakh Circassians.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Boğaziçi University began offering elective Adyghe courses in 2013.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] A significant debate persists in the Turkish diaspora regarding orthography of Adyghe.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Federation of Caucasian Associations (KAFFED) adopted the Cyrillic alphabet in 2004 to maintain continuity with the homeland, but other groups advocate for a Latin-based script to facilitate easier learning for Turkish speakers.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] This dispute intensified significantly when the Turkish Ministry of Education approved a Latin-based alphabet, called the ABX Latin Alphabet, for elective Circassian language courses in public schools, effectively creating a dual-alphabet system alongside the existing Cyrillic curriculum.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] KAFFED vehemently opposed this decision, arguing that it creates confusion and severs cultural ties with the autonomous republics in the Caucasus.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Demonstrations were at Ministry of Education offices across the country with slogans including "Hands off my alphabet," "We want our mother tongue's alphabet" and "How does Arabic in Latin letters sound?".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Ubykh people in Turkey, who originally possessed their own distinct language, largely integrated with the Adyghe during their exile and adopted the Adyghe language as their own.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Ubykh language went extinct in 1992; today Ubykh people speak Adyghe or Turkish.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe State University is working to document Adyghe language and folklore in Turkey.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Circassian community in Israel, concentrated in the Circassian towns of Kfar Kama and Rehaniya, is considered to have one of the highest levels of language maintenance in the diaspora.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe serves as the language of daily communication in the home, school, and public spaces.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 1958-1959, Israeli Circassians made contact for the first time with Circassians in the Caucasus and requested literary material in Adyghe, which they received.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 1976, the Adyghe language was introduced into the official school curriculum.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] It is a compulsory subject from 6th grade onward, and utilizes textbooks based on the literary standard of the Republic of Adygea.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Despite the dominance of the Shapsug dialect in speech, the written language taught in schools utilizes the Cyrillic alphabet and the Chemguy-based literary standard.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Kfar Kama is inhabited by the Shapsug tribe, while Rihaniya is inhabited by the Abzakh tribe.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Israeli variety of Adyghe also contains unique neologisms.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Even in diaspora communities with highly preserved spoken fluency, such as the compact Circassian settlements in Israel, literacy is a significant challenge; one survey showed that while 81.7% of respondents had advanced speaking proficiency, only 12% reported writing proficiency.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In Jordan, the Adyghe language has historically enjoyed a relatively privileged status, though it currently faces significant pressure, as Arabic has become the dominant language for the younger generation, and the Adyghe language is often restricted to symbolic functions or domestic use.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Consequently, Adyghe in Jordan serves more as a folkloric marker of identity than a functional tool for daily communication.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Adyghe language in Jordan is currently classified as severely endangered due to a rapid disruption in intergenerational transmission.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The decline of the language was triggered by migration, urbanization, and the dispersion of the Circassian population among the Arabic-speaking majority.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] For example, the expansion of Amman in the early 1900s transformed predominantly Circassian farming villages into diverse urban centres inhabited by Arabs, causing Circassians to become a minority in their original settlements.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Today, Arabic has almost entirely ousted Circassian as the primary language of communication within the home.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Surveys indicate that 21% of children use Circassian at home.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Because schools historically used Arabic as the sole medium of instruction, Circassian parents began speaking Arabic at home to ensure their children would not struggle academically.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe is taught in Prince Hamza Ibn Al-Hussein Secondary School, a school for Jordanian Circassians in Jordan's capital city of Amman.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] This school, established by Circassians with support from King Hussein of Jordan, is one of the first schools for the Adyghe communities outside Circassia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] It has around 750 Jordanian Adyghe students, and aims to preserve the Adyghe language and traditions among future generations.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The diaspora in Jordan has produced dictionaries and linguistic works, such as a Circassian-Arabic dictionary published in 1988.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Circassian Charity Association of Jordan also sponsors a school between Naur and Wadi Al-Seer that teaches the language.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Historically, various dialects were spoken by immigrants, including Shapsug, Bzhedug, (and Kabardian), but over time these dialects have merged.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Historically, the Golan Heights served as a centre for Circassian language preservation prior to the 1967 war.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the 1920s and 1930s, the "Circassian Society of Education and Union" in Quneitra published the newspaper *Mardj* in Circassian (using the Latin script), Arabic, and French, and established a school that taught the language alongside general subjects.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the late 20th century, the Circassian Charity Association in Damascus operated informal language circles to teach the Cyrillic script and preserve oral traditions.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] However, the language has declined due to the lack of state-supported education and the dominance of Arabic in all public spheres.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] After the Syrian defeat in the war, the Circassian population largely fled the Golan Heights region, which was occupied by the Israeli Army.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Many of Syria's ethnic Circassians have left the country and have repatriated to Adygea, Kabardino-Balkaria and Karachay-Cherkessia, as well as to partially recognised Republic of Abkhazia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Circassian American community is multilingual, speaking languages including English, Circassian (Adyghe, Kabardian), and Arabic.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] However, the community is currently experiencing a significant language shift away from their ethnic Adyghe language and toward English.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] English is the dominant language used in almost all public and social domains, utilized universally in the workplace and overwhelmingly with neighbors, non-Circassian friends, and even among Circassian peers.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Adyghe language remains preserved primarily within the home, specifically in intergenerational communication.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Circassian is predominantly spoken by the elder members of the community and is the primary language used when younger generations address their grandparents, representing over 52% of these interactions.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] A study found that a large majority of the New Jersey Circassian community (81.5%) agrees that learning the Circassian language is essential for maintaining their ethnic identity.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] However, some Circassian Americans have abandoned Adyghe fluency as redundant, focusing instead on Adyghe Khabze, traditional dances and folklore.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Circassian Benevolent Association (CBA) hosts a Sunday school where volunteers teach the Circassian language.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In recent years, growing political pressure and the criminalization of civil society initiatives in Russia have forced many scholars and language activists to relocate, shifting the epicenter of Circassian language activism and cultural preservation to countries abroad, including the United States.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Following the Circassian Genocide and expulsion in 1864, the majority of Adyghe speakers were scattered across the Ottoman Empire.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The language spoken in the diaspora has diverged from the literary forms in the Caucasus.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Diaspora communities often use Arabic or Turkish loanwords where the literary language uses Russian ones.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The linguistic divergence between the Adyghe language spoken in the historical homeland and the language spoken by the diaspora, particularly in Turkey and the Middle East, is the result of over a century and a half of isolated development.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] This isolation, combined with the mixing of various dialects and the strong influence of local languages like Turkish and Arabic, led to significant phonetic, lexical, and semantic differences.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Some native Adyghe words acquired entirely new meanings in the diaspora.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The word *гу*, which historically means "wagon" or "cart" in the literary language, has evolved to mean "automobile" or "car" among diaspora speakers.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Similarly, the word *ин* (big) is used in the diaspora to refer to an "elder," replacing the literary term *нэхъыжь*.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Due to intense influence of the Russian language, Russian loanwords in standart Adyghe are left exactly as is and not adapted to the language in terms of spelling or pronouncation.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Turkish linguistic influence led to the creation of calques (literal translations) for modern concepts.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In some extreme cases, diaspora speakers even attach Turkish grammatical suffixes, such as the past tense *-miş* or the subjunctive *-dı*, directly to Adyghe roots, though native speakers often recognize these constructions as "non-Adyghe".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] While the spoken and folkloric language of the diaspora evolved independently, this isolation has begun to diminish.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] With the advent of the internet and social media, the younger and middle generations in the diaspora are increasingly interacting with the Cyrillic-based literary language of the homeland.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] This exposure is initiating a slow but inevitable "literaturization" of the diaspora's language, gradually aligning their written and official communication with the literary standard.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] When conversing in Turkish, diaspora Circassians frequently embed native Adyghe terms to refer to specific traditional and unique cultural conventions, or use them as in-group slang.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Besides native vocabulary, the Adyghe language has accepted loanwsome ords from Turkic, Arabic, Persian, Russian and other languages.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] The appearance of Turkic loanwords in the Adyghe language can be dated to the 14th century due to interactions with the Golden Horde and Crimean Khanate.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] By the mid-19th century; Arabic words had begun to enter the language.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] Words such as *chapych* (kopeck) are pre-revolutionary loans from Russian.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/adyghe-language] In old borrowings, as a rule, the phonetic composition of borrowed words was adapted to the phonological system of the Adyghe language.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aer-language] After the Partition of India in 1947, the Muslim speakers of the language migrated to Pakistan, while the Hindu speakers stayed in India.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aer-language] Most of the Aer speakers in Pakistan live in Deh 333, near Hyderabad in lower Sindh.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aer-language] The language was formed in the Indian subcontinent during the Delhi Sultanate and Mughal Empire due to the influence of Persian, Arabic, and Turkish on Indian languages.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aer-language] A 1998 estimate concluded there were around 200 native speakers.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aer-language] Current estimates, however, put the number of speakers at 150, further cementing its 'endangered' status.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aer-language] Aer has been classified as one of the Gujarati languages.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aer-language] Ethnologue reports that the closest language is Kachi Koli and especially its dialects Katai Meghwar and Kachi Bhil, and that most Aer speakers are bilingual in Sindhi.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aer-language] Two varieties of Aer are Jikrio Goth Aer and Jamesabad Aer.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aer-language] Aer is commonly not written, but when it is, it is written in a variety of the Arabic script.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] Air Tamajeq, as well as other Tuareg languages, has traditionally and recently been written in three orthographies, with one or the other being the dominant orthography in specific contexts.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] These are Arabic script, Latin script, and Tifinagh (Traditional Tamajeq Tifinagh) script.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] Tifinagh has been the ancient and traditional script for writing of Tuareg.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] However, as Tuareg peoples have been a largely oral society, Tifinagh has only been used primarily for games and puzzles, short graffiti and brief messages.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] Arabic alphabet has come to be adopted with the spread of Islam among Tuareg people from the 7th century onward.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] Tuareg people, being an integral part of the Trans-Saharan trade, played the most significant role in spreading Islam to indigenous African communities further south, in the Sahel and Sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] Thus, Tuareg merchant, scholars, and clerics played a significant role in the teaching of the Arabic alphabet and its eventual adoption as part of what's today known as Ajami convention of writing, for writing of languages such as Songhay, Fula, and Hausa.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] Latin has been used for writing of Air Tamajeqand other Tuareg languages a lot more recently.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] Latin-derived scripts have been developed and adopted since the 19th century with the arrival of European Christian missionaries, colonial administrators, and linguists.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] The Latin script for Air Tamajeq is an "Alphabet".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] Tuareg languages, including Air Tamajeq, are the only languages that use Tifinagh in its original traditional form.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] The Traditional Tifinagh script is an "Abjad", meaning that vowels are not written or shown in any way, neither are geminated consonants.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] Only in the final position do letters *a* (ⴰ), *w* (ⵓ), *y* (ⵢ) serve as vowels in some contexts.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] Elsewhere, for example among the Imazighen (Berbers), the modified neo-Tifinagh, which is a full alphabet, is used.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] The Arabic script is an "Impure Abjad", meaning that some vowels are written using diacritics and some using actual letters, consonant letters serving as vowels depending on the context.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] Below is a sample text, translation of the Holy Bible, specifically the Gospel of Luke, chapter 1, verses 1 to 4 into Air Tamajeq.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/alexander-schlichter] Schlichter's grandfather, originally from western Germany (Württemberg), settled in what is the present-day Poltava Oblast of Ukraine in 1818.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/alexander-schlichter] Schlichter was ethnically one-quarter German and three-fourths Ukrainian.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/alexander-schlichter] Following studies at Kharkiv University, Schlichter joined a student the social democratic circle in 1891.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/alexander-schlichter] He was involved in the technical production of the illegal Bolshevik paper *Proletary* while it appeared in the Russian Empire (1904–1906).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/alexander-schlichter] After the October Revolution he succeeded Vladimir Milyutin as People's Commissar for Agriculture.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/alexander-schlichter] He also was People's Commissar for Food of the Russian SFSR, Commissar Extraordinary for Food in Siberia.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/alexander-schlichter] In 1919, he became People's Commissar for Food of Ukraine.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/alexander-schlichter] In 1920, he was Chairman of the Tambov Governorate Executive Committee, and was involved in suppression of the Tambov Rebellion.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/alexander-schlichter] In April 1927, he attended the Fourth Congress of Soviets as commissar of agriculture in the Ukrainian Republic.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/alexander-schlichter] There, he described 10% of the rural population of Ukraine as being "surplus".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/alexander-schlichter] After 1930 he was mostly involved in scientific activity.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/alexander-schlichter] He was a full member of the Communist Academy from 1930, an Academician of the Academy of Sciences of the Ukrainian SSR and from 1928, Academician of the Academy of Sciences of the Byelorussian SSR from 1933.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/alexander-schlichter] He became a Doctor of Economics in 1936.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/alexander-schlichter] From 1931 to 1938, Schlichter was Vice-President of Ukrainian Academy of Sciences, at the same time the director of the All-Ukrainian Institute of Marxism-Leninism and then president of the All-Ukrainian Association of Marxist–Leninist Institutions (VUAMLIN) from 1930 to 1936.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/alexander-schlichter] He was one of the initiators and active supporters of promoting the theories of Trofim Lysenko.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Chejne, *Aljamiado* or *Aljamía* is "a corruption of the Arabic word *ʿaǧamiyyah* (in this case it means foreign language) and, generally, the Arabic expression *ʿaǧam* and its derivative *ʿaǧamiyyah* are applicable to peoples whose ancestry is not of Arabian origin".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] During the Arab conquest of Persia, the term became a pejorative.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The systematic writing of Romance-language texts in Arabic scripts appears to have begun in the fifteenth century, and the overwhelming majority of such texts that can be dated belong to the sixteenth century.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] A key *aljamiado* text is the compilation *Suma de los principales mandamientos y devediamentos de nuestra santa ley y sunna* by the muftī of Segovia, of 1462.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In later times, Moriscos were banned from using Arabic as a religious language, and wrote in Spanish on Islamic subjects.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Examples are the *Coplas del alhichante de Puey Monzón*, narrating a *Ḥaǧǧ*, or the *Poema de Yuçuf* on the Biblical Joseph (written in Aragonese).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Aljamiado played a very important role in preserving Islam and the Arabic language in the life of the Moriscos of Castile and Aragon; Valencian and Granadan Moriscos spoke and wrote in Andalusi Arabic.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] After the fall of the last Muslim kingdom on the Iberian peninsula, the Moriscos (Muslims in parts of what was once Al-ʾAndalus) were forced to convert to Christianity or leave the peninsula.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] They were forced to adopt Christian customs and traditions and to attend church services on Sundays.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Nevertheless, some of the Moriscos kept their Islamic belief and traditions secretly, and this included the usage of Aljamiado.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In 1567, Philip II of Spain issued a royal decree in Spain, which forced Moriscos to abandon using Arabic on all occasions, formal and informal, speaking and writing.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Using Arabic in any sense of the word would be regarded as a crime.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] They were given three years to learn the language of the Christian Spanish, after which they would have to get rid of all Arabic written material.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Moriscos of Castile and Aragon translated all prayers and the (ʾAḥādīṯ of the Prophet Muhammad) into Aljamiado transcriptions of the Spanish language, while keeping all Qurʾānic verses in the original Arabic.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Aljamiado scrolls were circulated amongst the Moriscos.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Historians came to know about Aljamiado literature only in the early nineteenth century.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Some of the Aljamiado scrolls are kept in the Spanish National Library in Madrid.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] It is not an independent letter, but a special "dongara" consisting of a letter and a consonant (in other words, the repetition of a letter) to indicate a specific sound.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] These letters are only used in writing Arabic loanwords.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The Ladino equivalents for these letters are in accordance with the Judeo-Arabic orthographic traditions.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] This letter has a dual pronunciation, depending on the letter after it.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] For this reason, both in Aljamiado and in Ladino, two different letters are used to represent it.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Ladino, the pronunciation of this letter differs from its equivalent in modern Spanish.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Whenever the letter "D" is at the beginning of the word, or after a nasal consonant ("m" or "n"), or after a lateral consonant ("l"), pronounced as [d] and written with the letter "d".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In all other cases, it is pronounced as [ð] and written with the letter "d".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In old Spanish, the letter "X" was for representing the sound [ʃ].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] But in some words, especially those that start with "ex-", the pronunciation of this letter is [s], [ks] or [gz].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In the writing of Aljamiado, the Maghrebi script has been common, in which the placement and number of dot of on letters "fāʾ" and "qāf" are different from the conventional Arabic script, or the so-called "*Mashriqī* script" (مشرقي).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The letter "wāw" does not correspond to any exact letter in the Spanish Latin alphabet.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] This letter and its sound [w] are pronounced in certain digraphs and trigraphs.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Worded differently, there are diphthongs and triphthongs as result of certain vowel sequences, where the sound [w] is pronounced and the letter "wāw" is used to write it.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The letter "y" in the Spanish Latin alphabet is equivalent to "yāʾ" (ي).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] But this letter is also used to write some consonant sequences, especially consonant sequences that have a sound similar to [j] in their pronunciation.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In the Arabic language and alphabet, however, there are only 3 vowels, [a], [i], [u].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Arabic, these 3 vowels have both a short form, which is represented by diacritics *fatʾha*, *kasra*, and *ḍamma*, and long forms, which are represented by the letters *alif* (ا), *yaʾ* (ي), and *waw* (و).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Spanish, however, there is no difference between short and long vowels.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The vowel [a] is represented by the diacritic "◌َ".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The vowel [i] is represented by the diacritic "◌ِ".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The two vowels [o] and [u] are merged and are represented by the diacritic "◌ُ".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The vowel [e] is represented by the combination of fatʾha and *alif* "ـَـا".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The Hebrew alphabet, like Arabic, has both diacritics, known as niqqud, and the use of three letters *alef* (א), *vav* (ו), and *yod* (י).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In the Judaeo-Spanish alphabet, niqqud is not used, and only three aforementioned letters are used.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The vowel [a] is represented by *alif* "א".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The two vowels [e] and [i] are merged and represented by *yod* "י".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The two vowels [o] and [u] are merged and are represented by *vav* "ו".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Aljamiado, similar to Arabic and Persian, when the vowel is at the beginning of the word, *alif* (ا) is used as the vowel carrier, except for the [e] sound.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] For the [e] sound, a hamza is used as a vowel carrier, followed by *alif* (ا).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Judaeo-Spanish (Ladino) as in Arabic, *alif* "א" plays the same role.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] No distinction between unstressed or stressed vowels exist in Aljamiado manuscripts.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In the middle of the word, in Aljamiado, only diacritics (and for the case of [e] only a diacritic and an *alif* (ا) and in Judaeo-Spanish only one of the three previously mentioned letters are used.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Spanish, vowels sequences fall into two general types, diphthongs and Vowel hiatus.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] "diphthong" means that in practice, a pair of sequential vowels are read as a single vowel under one syllable.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] "Vowel hiatus" means that two vowels are read as two consecutive separate syllables.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The pronunciation of vowels and their writing are subject to certain rules in the Spanish Latin Alphabet, as well as in Aljamiado.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] As previously mentioned, in Aljamiado, there is no difference in writing between [o] and [u].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Judaeo-Spanish, there's no difference between [o] and [u], nor between [e] and [i].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] "Vowel hiatus" occurs when two strong vowels are sequential.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In such a case, each vowel is read as part of a separate syllable.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] "Diphthong" occurs when one vowel is weak and the other is strong.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In this case, Stress in pronunciation is on the strong vowel.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Of course, there are exceptions to these rules.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In order to better understand Aljamiado writing conventions, it is necessary to understand the pronunciation of Old Spanish and the evolution of the sounds of Spanish.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] That is why the manuscripts of Aljamiado are considered important sources for the study of Spanish linguistics.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The first thing that should be mentioned is that in Aljamiado, like Persian and other Arabic-derived alphabets, changes were made to the letters in the Arabic alphabet in order to show new consonants.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In other Arabic-derived alphabets, these changes were made by adding dots to the letters that most closely match an existing sound in Arabic alphabet.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] But in Aljamiado, this was done by gemination mark on the letters with the closest existing sound.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Gemination, in addition to this role, in Aljamiado also plays the role of geminating, like Arabic, something that is done in the Spanish Latin alphabet by writing letters twice.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] For example, "ب" produces a [b], but "بّ" produces a [p].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The Ladino alphabet also does the same thing with niqqud such as "Rafe" (רָפֶה) "◌ﬞ" or "Geresh" (גֶּרֶשׁ) "◌׳", for example "ב" produces the sound [b], and "בﬞ" or "ב׳" produce the sound [v].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Some letters simply adopted another value.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The phoneme /β/ was typically represented by the letter ب (b), though in some instances it was represented by the letter ف (f).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The plosive consonants were required to be aspirated; however, this aspect was lost in weaker positions such as the initial position of a word or an intervocalic position.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Aljamiado texts, the letter ط was utilized to represent the phoneme /t/ in initial and intervocalic positions where it was unaspirated, while the letter ت was utilized in postconsonantal positions to indicate the aspirated form of the phoneme.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Similarly, the letter ﻕ was used to represent the phoneme /k/ in initial and intervocalic positions where it was unaspirated, and the letter ﻙ was used in postconsonantal positions to indicate the aspirated form.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] However, according to the glossary of Abuljair, the aspiration of plosive consonants never ceased to occur in any position.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Spanish language, the letter "B" has two allophones.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] If the letter is at the beginning of the word, or after a nasal consonant ("m" or "n"), it is pronounced as [b].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The letter "v" also is pronounced as [v~β] regardless of position in the word.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Aljamiado, no distinction is made between any one of these.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The letter "baʾ" (ب) is used for all cases.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Judeo-Spanish, distinction is made between these two allophones.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Cases of [b] are written with the letter "beth" "ב".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Whereas the sounds [v~β] are written with the letter "beth" with Rafe or Geresh "בﬞ (ב׳)".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] As Arabic alphabet lacks a letter for the equivalent to the letter "P", the sound [p], in Aljamiado, a digraph has been created.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] This digraph consists of the letter "baʾ" and a shadda, "بّ".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] This is not an issue in Judeo-Spanish, as the letter "Pe" has two possible pronunciations of [p] and [f].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Thus for the sound [p], the letter "pe" (פ) is used.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] For the sound [f], the letter "pe" plus Rafe or Geresh (פﬞ (פ׳) / ף) is used.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Spanish, the letter "G" represents two pronunciations.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] If "G" is followed by "e", "i", or "y", it will have a "soft" pronunciation [x].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Otherwise, it will have a hard pronunciation [g].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Spanish, the letter "J" has pronunciation identical with "soft G".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In old Spanish, these two were pronounced as [ʒ‍~d͡ʒ].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Thus, the Aljamiado letter for both these sounds is reflective of this historic sound.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The letter "jim" (ج) is used, as opposed to "khaʾ" (خ).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Similarly in Judeo-Spanish, the letter "gimel" plus Rafe or Geresh (גﬞ (ג׳)) has historically been used.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Modern Judeo-Spanish (Ladino), unlike varieties of Spanish, this historic pronunciation has been preserved.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] However, due to contact and influence from other languages, namely Serbo-Croatian, Turkish, and French, a distinction between [ʒ‍] and [d͡ʒ] in orthography has come to dominance.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Namely that the former ([ʒ‍]) are shown with "zayn" Rafe or Geresh (זﬞ (ז׳)).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Similar to the letter "B", the letter "D" represents two allophones in Spanish.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] If the letter is at the beginning of the word, or after a nasal consonant ("m" or "n"), it is pronounced as [d].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] While this is not reflected in Latin alphabet, in Aljamiado manuscripts, as well as in Judeo-Spanish (not universally) is shown.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In instances where the pronunciation is [d], the letter "dal" (د) has been used in Aljamiado, and the letter "dalet" (ד) Judeo-Spanish.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In instances where the pronunciation is [ð], the letter "ḏal" (ذ) has been used in Aljamiado, and the letter "dalet" plus Rafe or Geresh (דﬞ (ד׳)) Judeo-Spanish.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Spanish Latin Alphabet, "r" versus "rr" denotes a difference in pronunciation, with the former being [ɾ] (Voiced alveolar tap), and the latter [r] (Voiced alveolar trill).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] This distinction is used in Aljamiado too with the use of shadda.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The letter "r" being shown with "raʾ" (ر), and the "rr" with "raʾ-shadda" (رّ).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] This distinction is not shown in Judeo-Spanish.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Both cases are shown with a single "resh" (ר).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In some regional varieties of Ladino, the distinction in pronunciation had ceased to exist as well.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] One of the notable evolutions in the Spanish language has been with respect to fricative-coronal consonants.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In old Spanish, the letter "z" was pronounced as [d͡z].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] It is thus written in Aljamiado with the letter "zaʾ" (ز).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Judeo-Spanish, the letter "zayin" (ז) is used.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] However, in modern Spanish, the pronunciation of the letter "z" has evolved in two manners.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In most dialects of European Spanish, the letter "z" today is pronounced identically as the soft pronunciation of the letter "c", as [θ].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Latin American dialects, the letter "z" is pronounced identically as the letter "s" and the soft pronunciation of the letter "c", as [s].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The letter "c" has two pronunciations in Spanish, based on rules and factors, hard and soft C.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] "c" is pronounced "soft" if it is followed by "e", "i", or "y", or if it is given a cedilla accent (ç).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In other cases, "c" is pronounced as "hard", as a [k].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In old Spanish, the soft pronunciation of "c" was as [t͡s].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Aljamiado, this letter was uniquely assigned the letter "sin" (س).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Judeo-Spanish, the letter "samech" (ס) was used.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] However, in modern Spanish, the soft pronunciation of the letter "c" has evolved in two manners.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In most dialects of European Spanish, the letter "c" today is pronounced identically as the letter "z", as [θ].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Latin American dialects, the soft pronunciation of the letter "c" is pronounced identically as the letter "s" and "z", as [s].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In old Spanish, the letter "s" was pronounced as [s] or [z], distinct from the soft pronunciation of the letter "c".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The digraph "ss" represented [s] as well, but has since been replaced with a single "s" in Spanish orthography.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] To reflect the difference between "s" and soft pronunciation of "c", in Aljamiado, the letter "shin" (ش) was given a new association and sound, and was used to write "s".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Similarly, in Judeo-Spanish, letter "shin" (ש) was used.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In modern Judeo-Spanish, in the centuries after expulsion of Jews from Spain, as the pronunciations of "c" and "s" merged independently of Spanish, confusion ensued for a few decades, with both "samech" (ס) and "shin" (ש) being used interchangeably.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] Today, the letter "samech" (ס) has won out and is used exclusively.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In old Spanish, the letter "x" had a pronunciation as [ʃ].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Aljamiado, the letter "shin" (ش) was used.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Judeo-Spanish, the letter "shin" has been used, historically with niqqud Rafe or Geresh (שﬞ (ש׳)).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In modern Spanish, the pronunciation of "x" has evolved.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In most cases, it is now pronounced as the letter "j" would, [x].
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] This is reflected in orthography as well.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Judeo-Spanish, the original pronunciation has been retained.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In some instances, especially in beginning of words as "ex-", the letter "x" has preserved an [s] sound, or a [ks] sound.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] In Judeo-Spanish this is reflected mostly by "gimel+zayin" (גז) and in some other words as "koph+samech" (קס).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/aljamiado] The practice of Jews writing Romance languages such as Spanish, Aragonese or Catalan in the Hebrew script is also referred to as *aljamiado*.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] Crimean Tatar is written in both the Latin and Cyrillic scripts.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] Before 1928, the Perso-Arabic script was the main orthography.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] Before the official introduction of the Common Turkic-based Latin alphabet by the Verkhovna Rada of Crimea in the 1990s, the Cyrillic alphabet was the main orthography.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] After the 2014 Russian annexation of Crimea, the Russian government required solely the use of the Cyrillic script.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] In 2021, the Ukrainian government began the transition to the Latin script.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] The Tatars of Romania use a different orthography.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] The letters Á, Ç, Ğ, Í, Î, Ñ, Ó, Ş, and Ú were added in the Dobrujan Tatar orthography in 1956.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] Crimean Tatars used the Perso-Arabic script from the 16th century to 1928, when it was replaced by the Latin alphabet based on Yañalif.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] The Crimean variant contained a couple of modified Arabic letters.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] Below table lists the letters used in Crimean Tatar Arabic script.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] The letter **ﻙ** (kef) was often used in place of **ﮒ** and **ﯓ**.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] The letter is actually **ﮒ**, some words with **ﮒ** are also readed as "y", to simplified this was the character by some writers used.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] The divergence of the three variants of the letter *vav* is one of the implemented conventions in the early 1920s into Crimean Tatar Arabic alphabet.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] Used as an *h* sound, and as a *e* sound (at the end of words).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] With the above mentioned modifications, the role of this letter expanded notably, in that the "final form **ـه ه** came to be used for the vowel sound *e* in the middle of the word in a lot more cases.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] Not an actual letter, but a common ligature.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] Letters shown with beige background are only used for writing of loanwords from Arabic language.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] They do not represent unique Crimean Tatar sounds, but sounds that are also written with other letters.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] Therefore, one of the implemented conventions in the early 1920s into Crimean Tatar Arabic alphabet was the acceptance (but not full enforcement, remaining optional) the removal of such letters.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] As per the 1921 and 1924 Crimean Tatar Arabic alphabet orthographic conventions, all vowels were to be written, as shown in the table below.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] The distinction between front and back vowel sounds "o, u, ı" versus "ö, ü, i" weren't marked.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] These were derived and understood from context and in following vowel harmony rules.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] Below general rules are noted in Crimean Tatar, same as other Turkic languages.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] In 1928, during latinisation in the Soviet Union, the Crimean Tatar Arabic alphabet was replaced by the Latin alphabet based on the Yañalif script.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] This alphabet contained a number of differences from the modern variant.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] Cyrillic for Crimean Tatar was introduced in 1938 as part of Cyrillization of languages in Soviet Union.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] It is based on Russian alphabet with no special letters.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] From 1938 to 1990s, that was the only alphabet used for Crimean Tatar.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] Modern Latin alphabet for Crimean Tatar was introduced in 1990s.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] It is based on Turkish alphabet with three special letters — **Q**, **Ñ**, **Â**.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] Its official use in Crimea was accepted in 1997 by Crimean Parliament.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] In 2021 it was approved by the government of Ukraine, to be adopted in education by September 2025.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] Tatar spoken in Romania has two distinct facets existing, interweaving and forming together the literary Tatar language "edebiy Tatarğa".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] One of these aspects is the authentic Tatar called "ğalpî Tatarğa" or "ğalpak Tatarğa" and the other is the academic Tatar language called "muwallímatça".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] Naturalization is shifting the spelling of academic speech sounds to authentic sounds following the patterns below, where a greater-than sign indicates that one sound changes to another.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] There is a total of 10 letters used to represent determinant sounds of which 9 mark authentic determinant sounds: a, e, i, î, í, o, ó, u, ú while the letter á is used for an academic vowel.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] The writing system registers authentic consonants with 17 letters: b, ç, d, g, ğ, j, k, l, m, n, ñ, p, r, s, ş, t, z and has three signs standing for the academic consonants: f, h, v.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] There are also two authentic semivowels: y, w.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] An old authentic Turkic consonant, the sound /ç/ represented by the letter ⟨Ç⟩ is rarely heard because authentic speakers of Tatar spoken in Dobruja spell it /ş/ as letter ⟨Ş⟩.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] As the written language most often follows the spoken language shifting ⟨Ç⟩ to ⟨Ş⟩, the result is that in Tatar spoken in Romania letter ⟨Ç⟩ and sound /ç/ are often treated as academic.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] The letters b, d, g, ğ, i, ó, u, ú, v can't occur at the end, as a last letter of the word (exception: *ald* and *dad*).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] Also the letter ñ can't occur as an initial letter of a word.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] The group of letters *aá* does not symbolize two adjacent vowels, being a writing convention that shows that the reading is done according to the first vowel in the group and the inflection of the word is done according to the second vowel in the group.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] For example, the reading of the word *kaár* "care" is identical to that of *kar* "snow", but in the ablative case they will become *kaárden* "of/from care", respectively *kardan* "of/from snow".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] The group of letters *áa* must be treated similarly.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] For example, the word *nikáa* "wedding" is read as "niká" and its dative will be *nikáaga* "to/to the wedding".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] In 1956 were the discussions about the alphabet problems of Dobrujan Tatar, which was regulated by Vladimir Drîmba, a well-known Turkologist, including other professors and teachers.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] The result was 33 letters, 10 of them vowels and 23 consonants.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] It was used in University of Bucharest, the Faculty of Foreign Languages and Literatures.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] The letter "Ç ç" is to see as "Č č" in the document of alphabet discussions, also "Ğ ğ" is more like "Ǧ ǧ".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] But they did appear as "Ç ç" and "Ğ ğ" in the grammar books.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] There was actually also the letter "Ţ ţ" (name: *ţe*).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] The letter "Ţ ţ" was originally an academic letter representing the sound voiceless alveolar affricate [ts] and naturalized to authentic as [s] "S s".
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] It is calculated that the letter "Ţ ţ" is fully naturalized to "S s", probably by Şukran Vuap-Mocanu in 1985, this means the words, which needed to be written with "Ţ ţ" are only written in authentic.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] Arabic script for Turkic languages was used since the 10th century by Kara Khanids.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] Dobrujan Tatar did use a variant of Chagatai alphabet.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] It was the same version as Ottoman Turkish alphabet.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] The writer Taner Murat, along with some others, revived the Arabic script, he did use it in some translations and did also make transliterations to Arabic script.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] Taner Murat did write in a different way from the traditional version.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] He did marked the vowels all the time by Arabic diacritics, like Xiao'erjing and different writing signs were used.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] Some letters unique to Arabic, were in the works of Taner Murat mostly replaced by other letters.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] The journal "Nazar Look" (نَظَرْ لُوقٌ‎), which was founded by Taner Murat, did also have a logo with Arabic script.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] The vowels are created with the harakats (ـَ / ـِ / ـُ‎) also with small-alif (ـٰ / ـٖ‎), the long vowels are represented by «ـَا / ـِی / ـُو‎».
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] The long vowels loose there function only when they are fallowed by «ـَ‎» and are without sukun (ـْ‎), these‌ (ـَا / ـَى / ـَو‎) are readed as „a“.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] The exceptional long vowels (aa, ee, ii) can be made by adding maddah (ـٓ‎) on the long vowel (ـَآ / ـِیٓ‎).
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] The letter «ا‎» or «ء‎» [randomly] is used as an initial letter when the vowel is the first letter of the word.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] Also when a vowel is fallowed by a vowel or when «ـِ‎» is fallowed by shaddah (ـّ‎), «ا‎» is written.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] There is a Cyrillic alphabet designed for Dobrujan Tatar by Taner Murat, including the letters Ә ә, Җ җ, Ң ң, Ө ө, Ў ў, Ү ү, І і.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] It was also used in translations with transliteration.
[src:crimean-tatar-alphabet/crimean-tatar-alphabet] Dobrujan Tatar has a version of Old Turkic script, which is designed by Taner Murat.
